# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ancient-maritime-history
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The *Abora I* originated as a school project in Germany using locally grown Giant (Miscanthus).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] All subsequent vessels were commissioned to boat builders from the Aymara nation living at Lake Titicaca in Bolivia; the same boat builders worked already for Thor Heyerdahl.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] As building material they used the very sturdy and durable Totora reed which is far better suited for this purpose.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The Abora (or Abora I, in retrospective) was designed, built and used between 1996 and 1999.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] It sailed from Alghero (Sardinia, Italy) to Piombino (Tuscany, Italy).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The Abora II sailed in 2002 across the Mediterranean: from Alexandria (Egypt) to Beirut (Lebanon), Cyprus and back to Alexandria.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] It thus became the first modern-time reed boat which managed to complete an extended round trip and then to return to the port of departure.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The departure at Alexandria coincided with the inauguration of the Bibliotheca Alexandrina, the new Alexandrian library; the Abora crew brought some gifts (books) from Thor Heyerdahl's Kon-Tiki Museum in Oslo, Norway in honor of the inauguration.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Thor Heyerdahl had also personally supported the preparation of the Abora I and II expeditions; by coincidence the launch of the Abora II took place on 18 April 2002, which turned out to be the day when Thor Heyerdahl died.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] With Abora III, Dominique Görlitz attempted the first ever crossing of the Atlantic from West to East with a reed boat.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Görlitz considered it possible that such events actually took place in antiquity.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] As a motivation, he particularly quoted the finding of traces of cocaine and nicotine in Egyptian mummies, including chopped tobacco leaves and the remains of a Mexican tobacco beetle in the mummy of Ramses II (1298–1213 BC).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Mainstream scholars have shown that there are possible Old World sources of cocaine and nicotine.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The finding of tobacco leaves became a popular topic in fringe literature and the media and it was seen as proof of contact between Ancient Egypt and the New World.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Compared to an East-West crossing, which Thor Heyerdahl successfully demonstrated in 1970 with the barely maneuverable reed boat Ra II, a west-east crossing of the Atlantic is much more difficult.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] This must be done further north along the Gulf Stream.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] However, the Gulf Stream does not flow evenly, but forms huge eddies.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Furthermore, the winds there blow inconsistently from all directions.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] This means that this crossing cannot take place as a practically pure drift, as in the case of the Ra II in the opposite direction, rather the reed boat must be able to cover longer distances by wind even under adverse conditions.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The hull of the boat was again manufactured in Bolivia (in 2006).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The boat was finalized one year later in New York.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The *Abora III* expedition started in New York on July 11, 2007.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] An initially supportive Azores high dissolved completely in early August, and the crew faced one storm after another.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Two of these storm lows reached hurricane strengths with wind speeds of up to 51 knots.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] These bad weather fronts affected the Abora III, but did not yet lead to serious damage.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] However, three side swords broke during the first storm, but this happened close enough to the American mainland that replacement swords could be delivered and replaced.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] In mid-August, after 500 km of a total of around 6000 km, a calm delayed the trip.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] A three-day hurricane then damaged the rear of the Abora III on August 27, 2007 in such a way that it had to be separated from the hull. during the subsequent 4 days, the crew reinstalled the intact rudder and moved the mast further towards the bow.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The modified Abora III could temporarily set full sail and even sail up to 90° to the wind.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] On September 4, the next storm with wind force 10 severely affected both the Abora III and an escort vessel approaching from the Azores.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Therefore, the crew abandoned the experiment on September 5, 2007, about 900 kilometres from the Azores, the 11-member crew and switched to the escort vessel.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The reed boat was left to the sea after cutting the strings that held the hull together.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] A message in a bottle thrown into the water before the boat was evacuated was found in the Bahamas in October 2010.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] This illustrates that a West-East crossing of the Atlantic requires an intact sailing ability of the boat (in contrast to the opposite direction: Thor Heyerdahl's Ra II was also badly damaged in 1970, but was still able to drift to America with the help of the Canary Current).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The aim of the Abora IV expedition was to retrace possible trade contacts between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Herodotus mentioned in his *Histories* trading contacts between the Egyptians and the Caucasus on the eastern Black Sea coast; according to him, especially metals were imported into Egypt via this route.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] According to the expedition leader Dominique Görlitz's assumption, tin and amber were also exported from Central Europe to Egypt via the Balkans and finally the Black Sea to the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Varna in Bulgaria was chosen as the starting point of the expedition both because of the place's historic significance (Varna Necropolis) and for practical reasons; the expedition received strong support from the Varna Archaeological Museum.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The final construction took place from May to August 2019 in Beloslav near Varna.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Due to the late delivery of the prefabricated reed bundles from Bolivia and due to extremely bad weather conditions in Bulgaria, the launch of the Abora was greatly delayed and the start of the expedition could only take place on August 16.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The Abora IV sailed through the Black Sea to Istanbul in Turkey, then through the Bosporus (on tow, for safety reasons), through the Marmara Sea and into the Dardanelles (again on tow) to Çanakkale (a modern harbor near ancient Troy), then onward into the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Here, the first station was the Greek island of Limnos, where the vessel managed to enter and to leave the prehistoric port of Poliochni without being supported by a tug boat.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] From there, it sailed on to Santorini, hereby managing to pass several straits between several Greek islands.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] During the expedition, Dominique Görlitz received the offer from the Turkish Ministry of Culture in Ankara to exhibit the reed boat in the Patara Archeology Park (near Antalya) as a permanent exhibit.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Thereupon it was decided to sail from Santorini straight to Kaş (a modern harbour near Patara) at the Lycian coast.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Here, the Abora IV arrived on 19 September; the entire distance from Varna to Kaş was covered in 34 days.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] As planned, the vessel is now on permanent display on the agora of the ancient city of Patara.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Like most experimental-archaeological projects, also the ABORA projects could only examine the technical feasibility of a proposed method.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Whether these methods were indeed exploited in the past, can only be clarified by archaeological finds.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The Abora expeditions specifically acclaimed to have reproduced an ancient navigation technology based on the use of leeboards.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] The expedition leader Dominique Görlitz presented various examples of such depictions (with and without leeboards) in his books and on the official project website.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Ethnological evidence for the use of large navigable rafts exists only from South America, where such rafts were in use also after the Spanish conquest.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] These rafts used so-called centerboards or guaras; they could be navigated even without a rudder.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Also Thor Heyerdahl conducted already some experiments using those guaras.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Therefore, Heyerdahl followed the ABORA expeditions with great interest until his death in 2002.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Positive appraisals of the ABORA projects came also from various other scientists, for instance Havva Iskan (Akdeniz University, Turkey, lead archaeologist at Patara, where the ABORA IV is now on permanent display).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] In 2007, during the ABORA III expedition, a critical article appeared in the German popular-scientific journal *Spektrum der Wissenschaft*.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] It quotes a German Egyptologist who doubts Görlitz' interpretation of details of boat depictions as leeboards, as well as his assumptions with regard to the age of those depictions, but does not offer an alternative explanation.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abora-expeditions] Specifically with regard to the Abora III expedition (attempt of a West-East Atlantic crossing), doubts are also expressed about alleged evidences for tobacco or cocaine use in ancient Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The **Abydos boats** are the remnants of a group of ancient royal Egyptian ceremonial boats found at an archaeological site in Abydos, Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Discovered in 1991, excavation of the Abydos boats began in 2000 at which time fourteen boats were identified.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] They are located alongside the massive mudbrick structure known as Shunet El Zebib, attributed to the 2nd Dynasty Pharaoh Khasekhemwy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Shunet El Zebib is one of several such "enclosure wall" constructions at this site dating back to the Early Dynastic Period, and is located nearly one mile from the royal cemetery of Umm El Qa'ab.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The University of Pennsylvania Museum and Yale University Expedition carried out the excavation of the Abydos boats.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Lines of mudbrick uncovered by blowing sand were first noticed in 1988 at a site a mile away from the royal tombs in Abydos.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] These brick remains were first thought to be just walls.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] However, it was later determined that they were the boundaries for more than a dozen ship burials from an early dynasty.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Each ship grave had its own brick boundary walls.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The outline of each grave was in the shape of a boat, and the surface of each was covered with mud plaster and whitewash.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Small boulders at the prow or stern of each grave represented anchors.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Because of the fragility of the boat remains, almost no excavation was done initially as the situation had to be carefully studied for future conservation.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] 10, which was slowly appearing due to apparent soil erosion, was the only boat that was initially investigated.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] For five days, archaeologists carefully examined the midsection of the ship.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] They uncovered wooden planks, disintegrated rope, and reed bundles.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Wood-eating ants had reduced much of the ship's hull to frass (ant excrement), but the frass had retained the shape of the original hull.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The midsection of this boat revealed the construction methods used and confirmed the oldest ‘planked’ constructed boat yet discovered.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The boat's construction revealed it had been constructed from the outside in, as there was no internal frame.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Averaging 75 ft long and 7–10 ft wide at their greatest width, these boats were only about two feet deep, with narrow prows and sterns.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Several boats were white-plastered, as were the Abydos tombs, and no.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Seams between planks were filled with reed bundles, reeds also covered the floor of each Abydos boat.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Without internal framing, some of these boats became twisted, as was unavoidable without an internal skeleton for support when out of the water.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The wood of the Abydos boats was local *Tamarix* – tamarisk, salt cedar – not cedar from Lebanon which was used for Khufu’s Solar Barque and favored for shipbuilding in Egypt in later dynasties.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Lebanon cedar was used for the poles and beams of the Umm el-Qa'ab tombs and had already been imported earlier; pigment residues hinted at bright colors.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] 29A cultural center.” This technology for ship construction persisted in Egypt for more than one thousand years and the standardization of this earliest phase of plank boat construction in Egypt is striking.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats were found in boat graves with their prows pointed towards the Nile.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Experts consider them to have been the royal boats intended for the pharaoh in the afterlife.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis that is about one mile from the Abydos boat graves where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are the predecessors of the great solar boats of later dynasties upon which the pharaoh joined the sun god Ra and together journeyed down the sacred Nile during the day.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] They would have had many of the important attributes and metaphors that were attached to the solar barques of later dynasties, and indeed perhaps should be called solar boats of an earlier design.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The Khufu ship, built for the Pharaoh Khufu – Cheops – ca.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] 2500 BC., is usually identified as the earliest solar barque.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] It was buried in a pit at the foot of the Great Pyramid at Giza.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The Abydos boat graves were adjacent to a massive funerary enclosure for the late Dynasty II (ca.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] 2675 B.C.) Pharaoh Khasekhemwy at Abydos which is eight miles from the Nile.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis at Abydos where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] However, these boat graves were established earlier than late in Dynasty II, perhaps for the afterlife journeys of Hor-Aha, the first king (ca.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] 2920–2770) of the First Dynasty of Egypt, or Pharaoh Djer also of Dynasty I.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Two more recently located mortuary discoveries have been identified as those of King Aha, who may have been the son of the famous King Narmer, to whom the first unification of Upper and Lower Egypt is often attributed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are not the only find of First Dynasty ships.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Nineteen boat burials were found at Helwan, but only four of these finds were published.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Six boat graves were found at Saqqara by Walter Bryan Emery and four of these finds were published.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Finally two full-sized model boats made out of clay are known from Abu Roash Hill.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Helwan (a suburb of Cairo on eastern side of Nile) contain a huge cemetery field 20 km south of Cairo adjoining Saqqara in which at least 10,000 tombs have been cataloged.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] The size of Helwan indicates a very large population for Early Dynastic Memphis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] Almost all the tombs date from Dynasty 0 through the Third Dynasty.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/abydos-boats] There are 19 elite tombs where 1st Dynasty funeral boat burials have been discovered that resemble those at Abydos, but little published information is available.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The **Achaemenid Empire** (/ə.ˈkiː.mə.nɪd/, *ə-KEE-mə-nid*; Old Persian: 𐎧𐏁𐏂, *Xšāça*, lit.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] 'The Empire' or 'The Kingdom') was an ancient Iranian empire founded by Cyrus the Great of the Achaemenid dynasty in 550 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] At peak, its territorial extent was roughly 5.5 million square kilometres (2.1 million square miles), making it the largest empire of its time.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Based in the Iranian plateau, it stretched from the Balkans and Cyrenaica in the west to the Indus Valley in the east, including Anatolia, Cyprus, Mesopotamia, the Levant, the South Caucasus, parts of Eastern Arabia, and large parts of Central Asia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the 7th century BC, the region of Persis, located in the southwestern part of the Iranian plateau, had been settled by Persian people.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persis, Cyrus rose and defeated Media, Lydia, and the Neo-Babylonian Empire, thus marking the establishment of a new imperial polity in the ancient Near East.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] While its conquests were largely successful in most regions, the Achaemenid Empire's attempts to expand into Greece proved extremely difficult over the course of decades of wars and multiple kings, ultimately resulting in its defeat in the Greek mainland.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 330 BC, amidst a Greek military campaign that began in 336 BC, the Achaemenid Empire was conquered in its entirety by Alexander the Great, who annexed it to his Macedonian Empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death, which sparked the beginning of the Hellenistic period in 323 BC, the majority of the former Achaemenid Empire's territories came under the rule of the Seleucid Empire and the Ptolemaic Kingdom.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Almost a century later, Iranian elites in the central plateau successfully reclaimed power from the Seleucids and established the Parthian Empire, which existed for nearly half a millennium before being succeeded by the Iranian Sasanian Empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of these systems were adopted and expanded upon by later empires in the Greco-Roman world and beyond.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is named after Achaemenes, who is credited as the progenitor of the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The term *Achaemenid* means "of the family of the Achaemenis/Achaemenes" (Old Persian: 𐏃𐎧𐎠𐎶𐎴𐎡𐏁, romanized: *Haxāmaniš*; a bahuvrihi compound translating to "having a friend's mind").
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Achaemenes was himself a minor seventh-century ruler of the Anshan in southwestern Iran, and a vassal of Assyria.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Around 850 BC the original nomadic people who began the empire called themselves the *Parsa* and their constantly shifting territory *Parsua*, for the most part localized around Persis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The name "Persia" is a Greek and Latin pronunciation of the native word referring to the country of the people originating from Persis (Old Persian: 𐎱𐎠𐎼𐎿, romanized: *Pārsa*).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian term 𐎧𐏁𐏂 *Xšāça*, literally meaning "The Kingdom", was used to refer to the Empire formed by their multinational state.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire was created by nomadic Persians.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were Iranian people who arrived in what is today Iran c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] 1000 BC and settled a region including north-western Iran, the Zagros Mountains and Persis alongside the native Elamites.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were originally nomadic pastoralists in the western Iranian Plateau.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire may not have been the first Iranian empire, as the Medes, another group of Iranian people, possibly established a short-lived empire when they played a major role in overthrowing the Assyrians.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids were initially rulers of the Elamite city of Anshan near the modern city of Marvdasht; the title "King of Anshan" was an adaptation of the earlier Elamite title "King of Susa and Anshan".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] There are conflicting accounts of the identities of the earliest Kings of Anshan.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Cyrus Cylinder (the oldest extant genealogy of the Achaemenids) the kings of Anshan were Teispes, Cyrus I, Cambyses I and Cyrus II, also known as Cyrus the Great, who founded the empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The later Behistun Inscription, written by Darius the Great, claims that Teispes was the son of Achaemenes and that Darius is also descended from Teispes through a different line, but no earlier texts mention Achaemenes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In Herodotus' Histories, he writes that Cyrus the Great was the son of Cambyses I and Mandane of Media, the daughter of Astyages, the king of the Median Empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus revolted against the Median Empire in 553 BC, and in 550 BC succeeded in defeating the Medes, capturing Astyages and taking the Median capital city of Ecbatana.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Once in control of Ecbatana, Cyrus styled himself as the successor to Astyages and assumed control of the entire empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] By inheriting Astyages' empire, he also inherited the territorial conflicts the Medes had with both Lydia and the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] King Croesus of Lydia sought to take advantage of the new international situation by advancing into what had previously been Median territory in Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus led a counterattack which not only fought off Croesus' armies, but also led to the capture of Sardis and the fall of the Lydian Kingdom in 546 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus placed Pactyes in charge of collecting tribute in Lydia and left, but once Cyrus had left Pactyes instigated a rebellion against Cyrus.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus sent the Median general Mazares to deal with the rebellion, and Pactyes was captured.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mazares, and after his death Harpagus, set about reducing all the cities which had taken part in the rebellion.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Lydia took about four years in total.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the power in Ecbatana changed hands from the Medes to the Persians, many tributaries to the Median Empire believed their situation had changed and revolted against Cyrus.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This forced Cyrus to fight wars against Bactria and the nomadic Saka in Central Asia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] During these wars, Cyrus established several garrison towns in Central Asia, including the Cyropolis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nothing is known of Persia–Babylon relations between 547 and 539 BC, but it is likely that there were hostilities between the two empires for several years leading up to the war of 540–539 BC and the Fall of Babylon.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In October 539 BC, Cyrus won a battle against the Babylonians at Opis, then took Sippar without a fight before finally capturing the city of Babylon on 12 October, where the Babylonian king Nabonidus was taken prisoner.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus is credited with freeing the Jews from the Babylonian captivity, permitting their return to Judah, and authorizing the rebuilding of Jerusalem, including the Second Temple.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 530 BC, Cyrus died and was succeeded by his eldest son Cambyses II, while his younger son Bardiya received a large territory in Central Asia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] By 525 BC, Cambyses had successfully subjugated Phoenicia and Cyprus and was making preparations to invade Egypt with the newly created Persian navy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Pharaoh Amasis II had died in 526, and had been succeeded by Psamtik III, resulting in the defection of key Egyptian allies to the Persians.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Psamtik positioned his army at Pelusium in the Nile Delta.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He was soundly defeated by the Persians in the Battle of Pelusium before fleeing to Memphis, where the Persians defeated him and took him prisoner.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After attempting a failed revolt, Psamtik III promptly committed suicide.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus depicts Cambyses as openly antagonistic to the Egyptian people and their gods, cults, temples, and priests, in particular stressing the murder of the sacred bull Apis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He says that these actions led to a madness that caused him to kill his brother Bardiya (who Herodotus says was killed in secret), his own sister-wife and Croesus of Lydia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then concludes that Cambyses completely lost his mind, and all later classical authors repeat the themes of Cambyses' impiety and madness.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, this is based on spurious information, as the epitaph of Apis from 524 BC shows that Cambyses participated in the funeral rites of Apis styling himself as pharaoh.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following the conquest of Egypt, the Libyans and the Greeks of Cyrene and Barca in present-day eastern Libya (Cyrenaica) surrendered to Cambyses and sent tribute without a fight.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cambyses then planned invasions of Carthage, the oasis of Ammon and Ethiopia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus claims that the naval invasion of Carthage was canceled because the Phoenicians, who made up a large part of Cambyses' fleet, refused to take up arms against their own people, but modern historians doubt whether an invasion of Carthage was ever planned at all.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, Cambyses dedicated his efforts to the other two campaigns, aiming to improve the Empire's strategic position in Africa by conquering the Kingdom of Meroë and taking strategic positions in the western oases.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] To this end, he established a garrison at Elephantine consisting mainly of Jewish soldiers, who remained stationed at Elephantine throughout Cambyses' reign.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Furthermore, in two inscriptions of Darius, Nubia is listed as one of the lands in the empire, and a Nubian delegation is depicted in Persepolis on the Apadana reliefs which visually present the lands of Darius’ empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] These suggest that Cambyses saw success in subduing Nubia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The events surrounding Cambyses's death and Bardiya's succession are greatly debated as there are many conflicting accounts.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to Herodotus, as Bardiya's assassination had been committed in secret, the majority of Persians still believed him to be alive.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This allowed two Magi to rise up against Cambyses, with one of them sitting on the throne able to impersonate Bardiya because of their remarkable physical resemblance and shared name (Smerdis in Herodotus's accounts).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ctesias writes that when Cambyses had Bardiya killed he immediately put the magus Sphendadates in his place as satrap of Bactria due to a remarkable physical resemblance.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Two of Cambyses' confidants then conspired to usurp Cambyses and put Sphendadates on the throne under the guise of Bardiya.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun Inscription, written by the following king Darius the Great, a magus named Gaumata impersonated Bardiya and incited a revolution in Persia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Whatever the exact circumstances of the revolt, Cambyses heard news of it in the summer of 522 BC and began to return from Egypt, but he was wounded in the thigh in Syria and died of gangrene, so Bardiya's impersonator became king.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The account of Darius is the earliest, and although the later historians all agree on the key details of the story, that a magus impersonated Bardiya and took the throne, this may have been a story created by Darius to justify his own usurpation.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Iranologist Pierre Briant hypothesises that Bardiya was not killed by Cambyses, but waited until his death in the summer of 522 BC to claim his legitimate right to the throne as he was then the only male descendant of the royal family.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Briant says that although the hypothesis of a deception by Darius is generally accepted today, "nothing has been established with certainty at the present time, given the available evidence".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun inscription, Gaumata ruled for seven months before being overthrown in 522 BC by Darius the Great (Old Persian *Dāryavuš*, "who holds firm the good", also known as *Darayarahush*).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Magi, though persecuted, continued to exist, and a year following the death of the first pseudo-Smerdis (*Gaumata*), saw a second pseudo-Smerdis (*Vahyazdāta*) attempt a coup.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The coup, though initially successful, failed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus writes that the native leadership debated the best form of government for the empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Macedonian king Amyntas I surrendered his country to the Persians in about 512–511.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Macedonia was part of Persian military operations initiated by Darius the Great (521–486) in 513—after immense preparations—a huge Achaemenid army invaded the Balkans and tried to defeat the European Scythians roaming to the north of the Danube river.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' army subjugated several Thracian people, and virtually all other regions that touch the European part of the Black Sea, such as parts of modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, and Russia, before it returned to Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius left in Europe one of his commanders named Megabazus whose task was to accomplish conquests in the Balkans.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian troops subjugated gold-rich Thrace, the coastal Greek cities, and defeated and conquered the powerful Paeonians.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Finally, Megabazus sent envoys to Amyntas, demanding acceptance of Persian domination, which the Macedonians did.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Balkans provided many soldiers for the multi-ethnic Achaemenid army.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of the Macedonian and Persian elite intermarried, such as the Persian official Bubares who married Amyntas' daughter, Gygaea.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Family ties that the Macedonian rulers Amyntas and Alexander enjoyed with Bubares ensured them good relations with the Persian kings Darius and Xerxes I, who was also known as Xerxes the Great.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian invasion led indirectly to Macedonia's rise in power and Persia had some common interests in the Balkans; with Persian aid, the Macedonians stood to gain much at the expense of some Balkan tribes such as the Paeonians and Greeks.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] All in all, the Macedonians were "willing and useful Persian allies.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Macedonian soldiers fought against Athens and Sparta in Xerxes I's army.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians referred to both Greeks and Macedonians as *Yauna* ("Ionians", their term for "Greeks"), and to Macedonians specifically as *Yaunã Takabara* or "Greeks with hats that look like shields", possibly referring to the Macedonian kausia hat.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt in 499 BC, and associated revolts in Aeolis, Doris, Cyprus, and Caria, were military rebellions by several regions of Asia Minor against Persian rule, lasting from 499 to 493 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the heart of the rebellion was the dissatisfaction of the Greek cities of Asia Minor with the tyrants appointed by Persia to rule them, along with the individual actions of two Milesian tyrants, Histiaeus and Aristagoras.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 499 BC, the then-tyrant of Miletus, Aristagoras, launched a joint expedition with the Persian satrap Artaphernes to conquer Naxos, in an attempt to bolster his position in Miletus, both financially and in terms of prestige.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The mission was a debacle, and sensing his imminent removal as a tyrant, Aristagoras chose to incite the whole of Ionia into rebellion against the Persian king, Darius I, who was commonly known as Darius the Great.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians continued to reduce the cities along the west coast that still held out against them, before finally imposing a peace settlement in 493 BC on Ionia that was generally considered to be both just and fair.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt constituted the first major conflict between Greece and the Achaemenid Empire, and as such represents the first phase of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Asia Minor had been brought back into the Persian fold, but Darius had vowed to punish Athens and Eretria for their support of the revolt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Moreover, seeing that the political situation in Greece posed a continued threat to the stability of his Empire, he decided to embark on the conquest of all of Greece.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The first campaign of the invasion was to bring the territories in the Balkan peninsula back within the empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian grip over these territories had loosened following the Ionian Revolt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 492 BC, the Persian general Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and made Macedonia a fully subordinate part of the empire; it had been a vassal as early as the late 6th century BC but retained a great deal of autonomy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 490 BC the Persian forces were defeated by the Athenians at the Battle of Marathon and Darius I would die before having the chance to launch an invasion of Greece.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes I (485–465 BC, Old Persian *Xšayārša* "Hero Among Kings"), son of Darius I, vowed to complete the job.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He organized a massive invasion aiming to conquer Greece.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] His army entered Greece from the north in the spring of 480 BC, meeting little or no resistance through Macedonia and Thessaly, but was delayed by a small Greek force for three days at Thermopylae.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] A simultaneous naval battle of Artemisium was tactically indecisive as large storms destroyed ships from both sides.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was stopped prematurely when the Greeks received news of the defeat at Thermopylae and retreated.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was a tactical victory for the Persians, giving them uncontested control of Artemisium and the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following his victory at the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes sacked the evacuated city of Athens and prepared to meet the Greeks at the strategic Isthmus of Corinth and the Saronic Gulf.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 480 BC the Greeks won a decisive victory over the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis and forced Xerxes to retire to Sardis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The land army which he left in Greece under Mardonius retook Athens but was eventually destroyed in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The final defeat of the Persians at Mycale encouraged the Greek cities of Asia to revolt, and the Persians lost all of their territories in Europe with Macedonia once again becoming independent.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes was assassinated in his bed, though ancient accounts conflict significantly.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The assassination is attributed by Greek and Roman sources to Artabanus, though a Babylonian tablet attributes it to Xerxes' son.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Xerxes I was assassinated, he was succeeded by his eldest surviving son Artaxerxes I.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was during his reign that Elamite ceased to be the language of government, and Aramaic gained in importance.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was probably during this reign that the solar calendar was introduced as the national calendar.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Artaxerxes I, Zoroastrianism became the *de facto* religion of the empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Persia had been defeated at the Battle of Eurymedon (469 or 466 BC), military action between Greece and Persia was halted.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes I took power, he introduced a new Persian strategy of weakening the Athenians by funding their enemies in Greece.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This indirectly caused the Athenians to move the treasury of the Delian League from the island of Delos to the Athenian acropolis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This funding practice inevitably prompted renewed fighting in 450 BC, where the Greeks attacked at the Battle of Cyprus.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Cimon's failure to attain much in this expedition, the Peace of Callias was agreed between Athens, Argos and Persia in 449 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes offered asylum to Themistocles, who was the winner of the Battle of Salamis, after Themistocles was ostracized from Athens.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, Artaxerxes gave him Magnesia, Myus, and Lampsacus to maintain him in bread, meat, and wine.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In addition, Artaxerxes I gave him Palaescepsis to provide him with clothes, and he also gave him Percote with bedding for his house.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes died in 424 BC at Susa, his body was taken to the tomb already built for him in the Naqsh-e Rustam Necropolis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was Persian tradition that kings begin constructing their own tombs while they were still alive.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes I was immediately succeeded by his eldest and only legitimate son, Xerxes II.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, after a few days on the throne, he was assassinated while drunk by Pharnacyas and Menostanes on the orders of his illegitimate brother Sogdianus, who apparently had gained the support of his regions.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus reigned for six months and fifteen days before being captured by his half-brother, Ochus, who had rebelled against him.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus was executed by being suffocated in ash because Ochus had promised he would not die by the sword, by poison or by hunger.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ochus then took the royal name Darius II.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' ability to defend his position on the throne ended the short power vacuum.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] From 412 BC Darius II, at the insistence of Tissaphernes, gave support first to Athens, then to Sparta, but in 407 BC, Darius' son Cyrus the Younger was appointed to replace Tissaphernes and aid was given entirely to Sparta which finally defeated Athens in 404 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the same year, Darius fell ill and died in Babylon.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] His death gave an Egyptian rebel named Amyrtaeus the opportunity to throw off Persian control over Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] At his death bed, Darius' Babylonian wife Parysatis pleaded with him to have her second eldest son Cyrus (the Younger) crowned, but Darius refused.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Queen Parysatis favoured Cyrus more than her eldest son Artaxerxes II.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Plutarch relates (probably on the authority of Ctesias) that the displaced Tissaphernes came to the new king on his coronation day to warn him that his younger brother Cyrus (the Younger) was preparing to assassinate him during the ceremony.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had Cyrus arrested and would have had him executed if their mother Parysatis had not intervened.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus was then sent back as Satrap of Lydia, where he prepared an armed rebellion.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus assembled a large army, including a contingent of Ten Thousand Greek mercenaries, and made his way deeper into Persia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The army of Cyrus was stopped by the royal Persian army of Artaxerxes II at Cunaxa in 401 BC, where Cyrus was killed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ten Thousand Greek Mercenaries including Xenophon were now deep in Persian territory and were at risk of attack.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] So they searched for others to offer their services to but eventually had to return to Greece.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II was the longest reigning of the Achaemenid kings and it was during this 45-year period of relative peace and stability that many of the monuments of the era were constructed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes moved the capital back to Persepolis, which he greatly extended.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, the summer capital at Ecbatana was lavishly extended with gilded columns and roof tiles of silver and copper.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The extraordinary innovation of the Zoroastrian shrines can also be dated to his reign, and it was probably during this period that Zoroastrianism spread from Armenia throughout Asia Minor and the Levant.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The construction of temples, though serving a religious purpose, was not a purely selfless act, as they also served as an important source of income.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] From the Babylonian kings, the Achaemenids adopted the concept of a mandatory temple tax, a one-tenth tithe which all inhabitants paid to the temple nearest to their land or another source of income.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II became involved in a war with Persia's erstwhile allies, the Spartans, who, under Agesilaus II, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] To redirect the Spartans' attention to Greek affairs, Artaxerxes II subsidized their enemies: in particular the Athenians, Thebans and Corinthians.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] These subsidies helped to engage the Spartans in what would become known as the Corinthian War.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 387 BC, Artaxerxes II betrayed his allies and came to an arrangement with Sparta, and in the Treaty of Antalcidas he forced his erstwhile allies to come to terms.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This treaty restored control of the Greek cities of Ionia and Aeolis on the Anatolian coast to the Persians while giving Sparta dominance on the Greek mainland.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 385 BC he campaigned against the Cadusians.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although successful against the Greeks, Artaxerxes II had more trouble with the Egyptians, who had successfully revolted against him at the beginning of his reign.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] An attempt to reconquer Egypt in 373 BC was completely unsuccessful, but in his waning years the Persians did manage to defeat a joint Egyptian–Spartan effort to conquer Phoenicia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He quashed the Revolt of the Satraps in 372–362 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He is reported to have had a number of wives.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] His main wife was Stateira, until she was poisoned by Artaxerxes II's mother Parysatis in about 400 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Another chief wife was a Greek woman of Phocaea named Aspasia (not the same as the concubine of Pericles).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II is said to have had more than 115 sons from 350 wives.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 358 BC Artaxerxes II died and was succeeded by his son Artaxerxes III.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 355 BC, Artaxerxes III forced Athens to conclude a peace which required the city's forces to leave Asia Minor and to acknowledge the independence of its rebellious allies.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes started a campaign against the rebellious Cadusians, but he managed to appease both of the Cadusian kings.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] One individual who successfully emerged from this campaign was Darius Codomannus, who later occupied the Persian throne as Darius III.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III then ordered the disbanding of all the satrapal armies of Asia Minor, as he felt that they could no longer guarantee peace in the west and was concerned that these armies equipped the western satraps with the means to revolt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The order was however ignored by Artabazos II of Phrygia, who asked for the help of Athens in a rebellion against the king.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes of Mysia also supported Artabazos and the combined forces managed to defeat the forces sent by Artaxerxes III in 354 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 353 BC, they were defeated by Artaxerxes III's army and were disbanded.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes was pardoned by the king, while Artabazos fled to the safety of the court of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] 351 BC, Artaxerxes embarked on a campaign to recover Egypt, which had revolted under his father, Artaxerxes II.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the same time, a rebellion had broken out in Asia Minor, which, being supported by Thebes, threatened to become serious.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Levying a vast army, Artaxerxes invaded Egypt and engaged in fighting with Nectanebo II.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After a year of fighting the Egyptian Pharaoh, Nectanebo inflicted a crushing defeat on the Persians with the support of mercenaries led by the Greek generals Diophantus and Lamius.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes was compelled to retreat and postpone his plans to reconquer Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Soon after this defeat, there were rebellions in Phoenicia, Asia Minor and Cyprus.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] , with a label in Greek (ΔΑΡΕΙΟΣ, top right) giving his name.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes committed responsibility for the suppression of the Cyprian rebels to Idrieus, prince of Caria, who employed 8,000 Greek mercenaries and forty triremes, commanded by Phocion the Athenian, and Evagoras, son of the elder Evagoras, the Cypriot monarch.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes initiated a counter-offensive against Sidon by commanding Belesys, satrap of Syria, and Mazaeus, satrap of Cilicia, to invade the city and to keep the Phoenicians in check.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both satraps suffered crushing defeats at the hands of Tennes, the Sidonese king, who was aided by 40,000 Greek mercenaries sent to him by Nectanebo II and commanded by Mentor of Rhodes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persian forces were driven out of Phoenicia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this, Artaxerxes personally led an army of 330,000 men against Sidon.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes' army comprised 300,000-foot soldiers, 30,000 cavalry, 300 triremes, and 500 transports or provision ships.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After gathering this army, he sought assistance from the Greeks.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Though refused aid by Athens and Sparta, he succeeded in obtaining a thousand Theban heavy-armed hoplites under Lacrates, three thousand Argives under Nicostratus, and six thousand Æolians, Ionians, and Dorians from the Greek cities of Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Greek support was numerically small, amounting to no more than 10,000 men, but it formed, together with the Greek mercenaries from Egypt who went over to him afterward, the force on which he placed his chief reliance, and to which the ultimate success of his expedition was mainly due.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The approach of Artaxerxes sufficiently weakened the resolution of Tennes that he endeavoured to purchase his own pardon by delivering up 100 principal citizens of Sidon into the hands of the Persian king and then admitting Artaxerxes within the defences of the town.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had the 100 citizens transfixed with javelins, and when 500 more came out as supplicants to seek his mercy, Artaxerxes consigned them to the same fate.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sidon was then burnt to the ground, either by Artaxerxes or by the Sidonian citizens.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Forty thousand people died in the conflagration.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes sold the ruins at a high price to speculators, who calculated on reimbursing themselves by the treasures which they hoped to dig out from among the ashes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tennes was later put to death by Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes later sent Jews who supported the revolt to Hyrcania on the south coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The reduction of Sidon was followed closely by the invasion of Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes III, in addition to his 330,000 Persians, had now a force of 14,000 Greeks furnished by the Greek cities of Asia Minor: 4,000 under Mentor, consisting of the troops that he had brought to the aid of Tennes from Egypt; 3,000 sent by Argos; and 1,000 from Thebes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He divided these troops into three bodies, and placed at the head of each a Persian and a Greek.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Greek commanders were Lacrates of Thebes, Mentor of Rhodes and Nicostratus of Argos while the Persians were led by Rhossaces, Aristazanes, and Bagoas, the chief of the eunuchs.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II resisted with an army of 100,000 of whom 20,000 were Greek mercenaries.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II occupied the Nile and its various branches with his large navy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The character of the country, intersected by numerous canals and full of strongly fortified towns, was in his favour and Nectanebo II might have been expected to offer a prolonged, if not even a successful resistance.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, he lacked good generals, and, over-confident in his own powers of command, he was out-maneuvered by the Greek mercenary generals, and his forces were eventually defeated by the combined Persian armies.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his defeat, Nectanebo hastily fled to Memphis, leaving the fortified towns to be defended by their garrisons.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] These garrisons consisted of partly Greek and partly Egyptian troops; between whom jealousies and suspicions were easily sown by the Persian leaders.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persians were able to rapidly reduce numerous towns across Lower Egypt and were advancing upon Memphis when Nectanebo decided to quit the country and flee southwards to Ethiopia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian army completely routed the Egyptians and occupied the Lower Delta of the Nile.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Nectanebo fleeing to Ethiopia, all of Egypt submitted to Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Jews in Egypt were sent either to Babylon or to the south coast of the Caspian Sea, the same location that the Jews of Phoenicia had earlier been sent.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this victory over the Egyptians, Artaxerxes had the city walls destroyed, started a reign of terror, and set about looting all the temples.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persia gained a significant amount of wealth from this looting.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes also raised high taxes and attempted to weaken Egypt enough that it could never revolt against Persia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] For the 10 years that Persia controlled Egypt, believers in the native religion were persecuted and sacred books were stolen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Before Artaxerxes returned to Persia, he appointed Pherendares as satrap of Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] With the wealth gained from his reconquering Egypt, Artaxerxes was able to amply reward his mercenaries.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then returned to his capital having successfully completed his invasion of Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his success in Egypt, Artaxerxes returned to Persia and spent the next few years effectively quelling insurrections in various parts of the Empire so that a few years after his conquest of Egypt, the Persian Empire was firmly under his control.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Egypt remained a part of the Persian Empire from then until Alexander the Great's conquest of Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] After the conquest of Egypt, there were no more revolts or rebellions against Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor and Bagoas, the two generals who had most distinguished themselves in the Egyptian campaign, were advanced to posts of the highest importance.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor, who was governor of the entire Asiatic seaboard, was successful in reducing to subjection many of the chiefs who during the recent troubles had rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the course of a few years, Mentor and his forces were able to bring the whole Asian Mediterranean coast into complete submission and dependence.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas went back to the Persian capital with Artaxerxes, where he took a leading role in the internal administration of the Empire and maintained tranquillity throughout the rest of the Empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] During the last six years of the reign of Artaxerxes III, the Persian Empire was governed by a vigorous and successful government.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian forces in Ionia and Lycia regained control of the Aegean and the Mediterranean Sea and took over much of Athens' former island empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, Isocrates of Athens started giving speeches calling for a 'crusade against the barbarians' but there was not enough strength left in any of the Greek city-states to answer his call.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although there were no rebellions in the Persian Empire itself, the growing power and territory of Philip II of Macedon in Macedon (against which Demosthenes was in vain warning the Athenians) attracted the attention of Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, he ordered that Persian influence was to be used to check and constrain the rising power and influence of the Macedonian kingdom.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 340 BC, a Persian force was dispatched to assist the Thracian prince, Cersobleptes, to maintain his independence.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sufficient effective aid was given to the city of Perinthus that the numerous and well-appointed army with which Philip had commenced his siege of the city was compelled to give up the attempt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the last year of Artaxerxes' rule, Philip II already had plans in place for an invasion of the Persian Empire, which would crown his career, but the Greeks would not unite with him.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 338 BC Artaxerxes was poisoned by Bagoas with the assistance of a physician.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III was succeeded by Artaxerxes IV Arses, who before he could act was also poisoned by Bagoas.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas is further said to have killed not only all Arses' children, but many of the other princes of the land.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas then placed Darius III, a nephew of Artaxerxes IV, on the throne.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III, previously the Satrap of Armenia, personally forced Bagoas to swallow poison.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 334 BC, when Darius was just succeeding in subduing Egypt again, Alexander and his battle-hardened troops invaded Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander the Great (Alexander III of Macedon) defeated the Persian armies at Granicus (334 BC), followed by Issus (333 BC), and lastly at Gaugamela (331 BC).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Afterwards, he marched on Susa and Persepolis which surrendered and was destroyed by fire in early 330 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persepolis, Alexander headed north to Pasargadae, where he visited the tomb of Cyrus, the man whom he had heard of from the *Cyropaedia*.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the ensuing chaos created by Alexander's invasion of Persia, Cyrus's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which it had been treated, and questioned the Magi, putting them on trial.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] By some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more an attempt to undermine their influence and display his own power than a show of concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior, showing respect for Cyrus.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] From there he headed to Ecbatana, where Darius III had sought refuge.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men murder Darius III and then declared himself Darius' successor, as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia leaving Darius' body in the road to delay Alexander, who brought it to Persepolis for an honourable funeral.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bessus would then create a coalition of his forces, to create an army to defend against Alexander.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander generally kept the original Achaemenid administrative structure, leading some scholars to dub him as "the last of the Achaemenids".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death in 323 BC, his empire was divided among his generals, the Diadochi, resulting in a number of smaller states.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The largest of these, which held sway over the Iranian plateau, was the Seleucid Empire, ruled by Alexander's general Seleucus I Nicator.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Native Iranian rule would be restored by the Parthians of northeastern Iran over the course of the 2nd century BC through the Parthian Empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Several later Persian rulers, forming the *Frataraka* dynasty, are known to have acted as representatives of the Seleucids in the region of Fārs.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] They ruled from the end of the 3rd century BC to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, and Vahbarz or Vādfradād I obtained independence c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] 150 BC, when Seleucid power waned in the areas of southwestern Persia and the Persian Gulf region.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] During an apparent transitional period, corresponding to the reigns of Vādfradād II and another uncertain king, no titles of authority appeared on the reverse of their coins.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The earlier title *prtrk' zy alhaya* (Frataraka) had disappeared.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Dārēv I (Darios I) however, the new title of *mlk*, or king, appeared, sometimes with the mention of *prs* (Persis), suggesting that the kings of Persis had become independent rulers.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the Parthian Arsacid king Mithridates I (c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] 171–138 BC) took control of Persis, he left the Persian dynasts in office, known as the Kings of Persis, and they were allowed to continue minting coins with the title of *mlk* ("King").
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid line would also be carried on through the Kingdom of Pontus, based in the Pontus region of northern Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Pontic Kingdom, a state of Persian origin, may even have been directly related to Darius I and the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was founded by Mithridates I in 281 BC and lasted until its conquest by the Roman Republic in 63 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The kingdom grew to its largest extent under Mithridates VI the Great, who conquered Colchis, Cappadocia, Bithynia, the Greek colonies of the Tauric Chersonesos and for a brief time the Roman province of Asia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Thus, this Persian dynasty managed to survive and prosper in the Hellenistic world while the main Persian Empire had fallen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Despite Greek influence on the Kingdom of Pontus, Pontics continued to maintain their Achaemenid lineage.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both the later dynasties of the Parthians and Sasanians would on occasion claim Achaemenid descent.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Recently there has been some corroboration for the Parthian claim to Achaemenid ancestry via the possibility of an inherited disease (neurofibromatosis) demonstrated by the physical descriptions of rulers and from the evidence of familial disease on ancient coinage.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great founded the empire as a multi-state empire, governed from four capital cities: Pasargadae, Babylon, Susa and Ecbatana.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids allowed a certain amount of regional autonomy in the form of the satrapy system.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] A satrapy was an administrative unit, usually organized on a geographical basis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] A 'satrap' (governor) was the governor who administered the region, a 'general' supervised military recruitment and ensured order, and a 'state secretary' kept the official records.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The general and the state secretary reported directly to the satrap as well as the central government.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] At differing times, there were between 20 and 30 satrapies.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great created an organized army including the Immortals unit, consisting of 10,000 highly trained soldiers Cyrus also formed an innovative postal system throughout the empire, based on several relay stations called Chapar Khaneh.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persepolis Administrative Archives provide many insights into the Achaemenid government system.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Found at Persepolis in the 1930s, they are mostly in Elamite; the remains of more than 10,000 of these cuneiform documents have been uncovered.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Aramaic is represented by about 1,000 or more original records.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Only one tablet in Old Persian has been identified so far.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, many seals and seal impressions are found in these Persepolis archives.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] These documents represent administrative activity and flow of data in Persepolis over more than fifty consecutive years (509–457 BC).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian daric was the first gold coin which, along with a similar silver coin, the siglos, introduced the bimetallic monetary standard of the Achaemenids, which has continued until today.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was accomplished by Darius I, who reinforced the empire and expanded Persepolis as a ceremonial capital; he revolutionized the economy by placing it on the silver and gold coinage.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius also introduced a regulated and sustainable tax system that was precisely tailored to each satrapy, based on their supposed productivity and their economic potential.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] For instance, Babylon was assessed for the highest amount and for a startling mixture of commodities – 1,000 silver talents, four months' supply of food for the army.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] India was clearly already fabled for its gold; Egypt was known for the wealth of its crops; it was to be the granary of the Persian Empire (as later of Rome's) and was required to provide 120,000 measures of grain in addition to 700 talents of silver.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was exclusively a tax levied on subject peoples.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] There is evidence that conquered and rebellious enemies could be sold into slavery.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alongside its other innovations in administration and taxation, the Achaemenids may have been the first government in the ancient Near East to register private slave sales and tax them using an early form of sales tax.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Other accomplishments of Darius' reign included the codification of the *dāta* (a universal legal system which would become the basis of later Iranian law), and the construction of a new capital at Persepolis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under the Achaemenids, trade was extensive and there was an efficient infrastructure that facilitated the exchange of commodities in the far reaches of the empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tariffs on trade, along with agriculture and tribute, were major sources of revenue for the empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The satrapies were linked by a 2,500-kilometer highway, the most impressive stretch being the Royal Road from Susa to Sardis, built under the command of Darius I.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It connected the Iranian Plateau to Central Asia and the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] It featured stations and caravanserais at specific intervals.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] The relays of mounted couriers (the angarium) could reach the remotest of areas in fifteen days.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus observes that "there is nothing in the world that travels faster than these Persian couriers.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Alexander's conquests, this highway allowed for the spread of cultural syncretic fusions like Greco-Buddhism into Central Asia and China, as well as empires like the Kushan, Indo-Greek and Parthian to profit from trade between East and West.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p01] This route was greatly rehabilitated and formalized during the Abbasid Caliphate, during which it developed into a major component of the famed Silk Road.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite its humble origins in Persis, the empire reached an enormous size under the leadership of Cyrus the Great.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus created a multi-state empire where he allowed regional rulers, satraps, to rule as his proxy over a certain designated area of his empire called a satrapy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The basic rule of governance was based upon loyalty and obedience of each satrapy to the central power, or the king, and compliance with tax laws.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus managed to create a strong land army, using it to advance in his campaigns in Babylonia, Lydia, and Asia Minor, which after his death was used by his son Cambyses II, in Egypt against Psamtik III.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus would die battling a local Iranian insurgency in the empire, before he could have a chance to develop a naval force.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] That task would fall to Darius I, who would officially give Persians their own royal navy to allow them to engage their enemies on multiple seas of this vast empire, from the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea, to the Persian Gulf, Ionian Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid infantry consisted of three groups: the Immortals, the Sparabara, and the Takabara, though in the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, a fourth group, the Cardaces, were introduced.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Immortals were described by Herodotus as being heavy infantry, led by Hydarnes II, that were kept constantly at a strength of exactly 10,000 men.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] He claimed that the unit's name stemmed from the custom that every killed, seriously wounded, or sick member was immediately replaced with a new one, maintaining the numbers and cohesion of the unit.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They had wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, and bow and arrows.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Underneath their robes they wore scale armour coats.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The spear counterbalances of the common soldiery were of silver; to differentiate commanding ranks, the officers' spear butt-spikes were golden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Surviving Achaemenid colored glazed bricks and carved reliefs represent the Immortals as wearing elaborate robes, hoop earrings and gold jewellery, though these garments and accessories were most likely worn only for ceremonial occasions.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were usually the first to engage in hand-to-hand combat with the enemy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although not much is known about them today, it is believed that they were the backbone of the Persian army who formed a shield wall and used their two-metre-long spears to protect more vulnerable troops such as archers from the enemy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were taken from the full members of Persian society, were trained from childhood to be soldiers and when not called out to fight on campaigns in distant lands they practised hunting on the vast plains of Persia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, when all was quiet and the *Pax Persica* held true, the Sparabara returned to normal life farming the land and grazing their herds.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Because of this, they lacked true professional quality on the battlefield, yet they were well trained and courageous to the point of holding the line in most situations long enough for a counter-attack.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They were armoured with quilted linen and carried large rectangular wicker shields as a form of light maneuverable defence.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] This, however, left them at a severe disadvantage against heavily armoured opponents such as the hoplite, and their two-metre-long spear was not able to give the Sparabara ample range to plausibly engage a trained phalanx.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The wicker shields were able to effectively stop arrows but not strong enough to protect the soldier from spears.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, the Sparabara could deal with most other infantry, including trained units from the East.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenids relied heavily on archery.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Major contributing nations were the Scythians, Medes, Persians, and the Elamites.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The composite bow was used by the Persians and Medes, who adopted it from the Scythians and transmitted it to other nations, including the Greeks.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid armies typically used socketed, three-bladed (also known as trilobate or Scythian) arrowheads.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] These arrowheads were cast from leaded tin-bronze, which made them amenable to mass-production unlike the wrought iron arrowheads of the period that had to be individually forged.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were a rare unit who were a tough type of peltasts.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They tended to fight with their own native weapons which would have included a crescent-shaped light wickerwork shield and axes as well as light linen cloth and leather.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were recruited from territories that incorporated modern Iran.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian cavalry was crucial for conquering nations and maintained its importance in the Achaemenid army to the last days of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The cavalry was separated into four groups.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers, horse cavalry, the camel cavalry, and the war elephants.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, the chariot archer had become merely a ceremonial part of the Persian army, yet in the early years of the Empire, their use was widespread.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers were armed with lances, bows, arrows, swords, and scale armour.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses were also suited with scale armour similar to scale armour of the Sassanian cataphracts.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariots would contain imperial symbols and decorations.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses used by the Achaemenids for cavalry were often suited with scale armour, like most cavalry units.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The riders often had the same armour as Infantry units, wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, bow and arrow, and scale armour coats.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was different, because the camels and sometimes the riders, were provided little protection against enemies, yet when they were offered protection, they would have lances, swords, bow, arrow, and scale armour.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was first introduced into the Persian army by Cyrus the Great, at the Battle of Thymbra.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The elephant was most likely introduced into the Persian army by Darius I after his conquest of the Indus Valley.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Elephants may have been used in Greek campaigns by Darius and Xerxes I, but Greek accounts only mention 15 of them being used at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Since its foundation by Cyrus, the Persian empire had been primarily a land empire with a strong army but void of any actual naval forces.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] By the 5th century BC, this was to change, as the empire came across Greek and Egyptian forces, each with their own maritime traditions and capabilities.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I was the first Achaemenid king to invest in a Persian fleet.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even by then no true "imperial navy" had existed either in Greece or Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persia would become the first empire, under Darius, to inaugurate and deploy the first regular imperial navy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite this achievement, the personnel for the imperial navy would not come from Iran, but were often Phoenicians (mostly from Sidon), Egyptians and Greeks chosen by Darius the Great to operate the empire's combat vessels.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] At first the ships were built in Sidon by the Phoenicians; the first Achaemenid ships measured about 40 meters in length and 6 meters in width, able to transport up to 300 Persian troops at any one trip.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Soon, other states of the empire were constructing their own ships, each incorporating slight local preferences.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships eventually found their way to the Persian Gulf and Persian naval forces laid the foundation for a strong Persian maritime presence there.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persians also had ships often of a capacity 100 to 200 troops patrolling the empire's various rivers including the Karun, Tigris and Nile in the west, as well as the Indus.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid navy established bases located along the Karun, and in Bahrain, Oman, and Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian fleet was not only used for peace-keeping purposes along the Karun but also opened the door to trade with India via the Persian Gulf.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius's navy was in many ways a world power at the time, but it would be Artaxerxes II who in the summer of 397 BC would build a formidable navy, as part of a rearmament which would lead to his decisive victory at Knidos in 394 BC, re-establishing Achaemenid power in Ionia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II would also use his navy to later on quell a rebellion in Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The construction material of choice was wood, but some armoured Achaemenid ships had metallic blades on the front, often meant to slice enemy ships using the ship's momentum.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Naval ships were also equipped with hooks on the side to grab enemy ships, or to negotiate their position.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships were propelled by sails or manpower.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships the Persians created were unique.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] As far as maritime engagement, the ships were equipped with two mangonels that would launch projectiles such as stones, or flammable substances.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Xenophon describes his eyewitness account of a massive military bridge created by joining 37 Persian ships across the Tigris.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persians used each boat's buoyancy to support a connected bridge above which supply could be transferred.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus also gives many accounts of the Persians using ships to build bridges.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I, in an attempt to subdue the Scythian horsemen north of the Black Sea, crossed over at the Bosphorus, using an enormous bridge made by connecting Achaemenid boats, then marched up to the Danube, crossing it by means of a second boat bridge.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The bridge over the Bosphorus essentially connected the nearest tip of Asia to Europe, encompassing at least some 1000 meters of open water if not more.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, a similar boat bridge would be constructed by Xerxes I, in his invasion of Greece.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians failed to capture the Greek city-states completely, the tradition of maritime involvement was carried down by the Persian kings, most notably Artaxerxes II.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, when Alexander invaded Persia and during his advancement into India, he took a page from the Persian art of war, by having Hephaestion and Perdiccas construct a similar boat-bridge at the Indus river in India in the spring of 327 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Cyrus II and Darius I, and as long as the seat of government was still at Susa in Elam, the language of the chancellery was Elamite.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] This is primarily attested in the Persepolis fortification and treasury tablets that reveal details of the day-to-day functioning of the empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the grand rock-face inscriptions of the kings, the Elamite texts are always accompanied by Akkadian (Babylonian dialect) and Old Persian inscriptions, and it appears that in these cases that the Elamite texts are translations of the Old Persian ones.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] It is then likely that although Elamite was used by the capital government in Susa, it was not a standardized language of government everywhere in the empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The use of Elamite is not attested after 458 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Following the conquest of Mesopotamia, the Aramaic language (as used in that territory) was adopted as a "vehicle for written communication between the different regions of the vast empire with its different peoples and languages.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] In 1955, Richard Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an official language, noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the *lingua franca* of the Achaemenid empire, suggesting that the use of Aramaic language in Achaemenid empire was more widespread than generally thought.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many centuries after the fall of the empire, Aramaic script and—as ideograms—Aramaic vocabulary would survive as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi writing system.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although Old Persian also appears on some seals and art objects, that language is attested primarily in the Achaemenid inscriptions of Western Iran, suggesting then that Old Persian was the common language of that region.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] When the occasion demanded, Achaemenid administrative correspondence was conducted in Greek, making it a widely used bureaucratic language.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even though the Achaemenids had extensive contacts with the Greeks and vice versa, and had conquered many of the Greek-speaking areas both in Europe and Asia Minor during different periods of the empire, the native Old Iranian sources provide no indication of Greek linguistic influence.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, there is plenty of evidence (in addition to the accounts of Herodotus) that Greeks, apart from being deployed and employed in the core regions of the empire, also evidently lived and worked in the heartland of the Achaemenid Empire, namely Iran.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, Greeks were part of the various ethnicities that constructed Darius' palace in Susa, apart from the Greek inscriptions found nearby there, and one short Persepolis tablet written in Greek.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus mentions that the Persians were invited to great birthday feasts (Herodotus, *Histories* 8), which would be followed by many desserts, a treat which they reproached the Greeks for omitting from their meals.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] He also observed that the Persians drank wine in large quantities and used it even for counsel, deliberating on important affairs when drunk, and deciding the next day, when sober, whether to act on the decision or set it aside.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Religious toleration has been described as a "remarkable feature" of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Hebrew Bible reports that Persian king Cyrus the Great released the Jewish people from the Babylonian captivity in 539–530 BC and permitted them to return to their homeland.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus the Great assisted in the restoration of the sacred places of various cities, including to rebuild the Israelites’ Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] It was during the Achaemenid period that Zoroastrianism reached southwestern Iran, where it came to be accepted by the rulers and through them became a defining element of Persian culture.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The religion was not only accompanied by a formalization of the concepts and divinities of the traditional Iranian pantheon but also introduced several novel ideas, including that of free will.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Mithra was worshipped in the Empire; his temples and symbols were the most widespread, most people bore names related to him and most festivals were dedicated to him.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Artaxerxes I and Darius II, the Greek historian Herodotus wrote: "[the Persians] have no images of the gods, no temples nor altars, and consider the use of them a sign of folly.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] This comes, I think, from their not believing the gods to have the same nature with men, as the Greeks imagine." He claims the Persians offer sacrifice to: "the sun and moon, to the earth, to fire, to water, and to the winds.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] These are the only gods whose worship has come down to them from ancient times.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] At a later period, they began the worship of Urania, which they borrowed from the Arabians and Assyrians.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Babylonian scholar and priest Berosus records—although writing over seventy years after the reign of Artaxerxes II—that the emperor had been the first to make cult statues of divinities and have them placed in temples in many of the major cities of the empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Berosus also substantiates Herodotus when he says the Persians knew of no images of gods until Artaxerxes II erected those images.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] On the means of sacrifice, Herodotus adds "they raise no altar, light no fire, pour no libations." Herodotus also observed that "no prayer or offering can be made without a magus present".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The position of women in the Achaemenid Empire varied depending on the culture to which they belonged and therefore differed by region.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The hierarchy of royal women at the Persian court was ranked as follows: the king's mother, then the queen, the king's daughters, the king's concubines, and the other women of the royal palace.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king normally married a female member of the royal family or a Persian noblewoman related to a satrap or another important Persian man; it was permitted for members of the royal family to marry relatives, but there is no evidence for marriage between closer family members than half-siblings.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king's concubines were often either slaves, sometimes prisoners of war, or foreign princesses, whom the king did not marry because they were foreigners, and whose children did not have the right to inherit the throne.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Greek sources accuse the king of having hundreds of concubines secluded in a harem.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is no archeological evidence supporting the existence of a harem, or the seclusion of women from contact with men, at the Persian court.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The royal women joined the king at breakfast and dinner and accompanied him on his journeys.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They may have participated in the royal hunt, as well as during the royal banquets.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus relates how the Persian envoys at the Macedonian court demanded the presence of women during a banquet because it was the custom for women to participate in the banquets in their own country.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The queen may have attended the king's audience, and archeological evidence shows that she gave her own audiences, at least for female supplicants.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal women and noblewomen at court could travel on their own, accompanied by both male and female staff, own and manage their own fortune, land, and business.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Depictions of Persian women show them with long dresses and veils which did not cover their faces or their hair, only flowing down over their neck at the back of the head as an ornament.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic Achaemenid women were given an education in subjects that did not appear compatible with seclusions, such as horsemanship and archery.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women held and managed vast estates and workshops and employed large numbers of servants and professional laborers.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women do not seem to have lived in seclusion from men, since it is known that they appeared in public and traveled with their husbands, participated in hunting and in feasts.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chief wife of a royal or aristocratic man did not live in seclusion, as it is clearly stated that wives customarily accompanied their husbands at dinner banquets.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] They left the banquet when the "women entertainers" came in and the men began "merrymaking".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] No woman ever ruled the Achaemenid Empire, as monarch or as regent, but some queen's consorts are known to have had influence over the affairs of state, notably Atossa and Parysatis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is not evidence of any women being employed as an official in the administration or within religious service; however, there are plenty of archeological evidence of women being employed as free labourers in Persepolis, where they worked alongside men.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women could be employed as the leaders of their workforce, known by the title *arraššara pašabena*, which were then given a higher salary than the male workers of their workforce.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Female laborers were given less than men.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Qualified workers within the crafts were given equal pay regardless of their sex.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women are abundant in religious context in the cuneiform sources from late Achaemenid and Hellenistic Babylon.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid architecture included large cities, temples, palaces, and mausolea such as the Tomb of Cyrus the Great.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The quintessential feature of its architecture was its eclectic nature, with elements of Median, Assyrian, and Asiatic Greek all incorporated, yet maintaining a unique Persian identity seen in the finished products.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Its influence pervades the regions ruled by the Achaemenids, from the Mediterranean shores to India, especially with its emphasis on monumental stone-cut design and gardens subdivided by water-courses.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid art includes frieze reliefs, metalwork such as the Oxus Treasure, decoration of palaces, glazed brick masonry, fine craftsmanship (masonry, carpentry, etc.), and gardening.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians drew artists from all corners of their empire, incorporating their styles and techniques, they did not merely produce a combination of styles, but a synthesis of a new, unique Persian style.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] One of the most remarkable examples of both Achaemenid architecture and art is the grand palace of Persepolis, and its detailed workmanship, coupled with its grand scale.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many Achaemenid rulers built tombs for themselves.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The most famous, Naqsh-e Rostam, is an ancient necropolis located about 12 km north-west of Persepolis, with the tombs of four of the kings of the dynasty are carved in this mountain: Darius I, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I and Darius II.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Other kings constructed their own tombs elsewhere.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II and Artaxerxes III preferred to carve their tombs beside their spring capital Persepolis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The left tomb belongs to Artaxerxes II and the right tomb belongs to Artaxerxes III, the last Achaemenid king to have a tomb.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The tomb of the founder of the Achaemenid dynasty, Cyrus the Great, was built in Pasargadae (now a world heritage site).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has been referred to as the first “world empire” as it contained in the words of Persian kings “many people and many languages”.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The diverse groups which made up the empire enjoyed a great deal of legal and cultural autonomy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has also left a lasting impression on the heritage and cultural identity of Asia and the Middle East, and influenced the development and structure of future empires.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] In fact, the Greeks, and later on the Romans, adopted the best features of the Persian method of governing an empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian model of governance was particularly formative in the expansion and maintenance of the Abbasid Caliphate, whose rule is widely considered the period of the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire is noted in Western history as the antagonist of the Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars and for the emancipation of the Jewish exiles in Babylon.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The historical mark of the empire went far beyond its territorial and military influences and included cultural, social, technological and religious influences as well.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, many Athenians adopted Achaemenid customs in their daily lives in a reciprocal cultural exchange, some being employed by or allied to the Persian kings.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The impact of the Edict of Cyrus is mentioned in Judeo-Christian texts, and the empire was instrumental in the spread of Zoroastrianism as far east as China.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] The empire also set the tone for the politics, heritage and history of Iran (also known as Persia).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-empire-p02] Hegel in his work *The Philosophy of History* introduces the Persian Empire as the "first empire that passed away" and its people as the "first historical people" in history.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The **Achaemenid navy** (Old Persian: 𐎴𐎠𐎺 *nāva*) was the principal naval force of the Achaemenid Empire which existed between 525 BC and 330 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] In Old Persian, the written language of Achaemenid inscriptions, the word used to refer to the 'navy' or 'fleet' was "*nāva*", a noun in plural feminine nominative form.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] It is of the same root of Indo-European for words such as "navy" and "navigate".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] In modern usage of Persian language, the word has retained its form and meaning (lit.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] No relevant primary documents have been found about it, nor have any ruins of Persian naval installations or remains of ships been excavated.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] While independent Persian tradition is lost, all we know about the Achaemenid navy is recorded by ancient Greek historians like Herodotus.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Scholars categorize the record of operation of the navy to two distinct periods from 525 to 479, and from 479 to 330 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Cambyses founded the navy for conquest of Egypt in the Battle of Pelusium.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] After him, Darius I deployed the navy to strengthen dominance over the coast of Asia Minor, as well as its adjacent islands.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] During reign of Darius, Persians captured Samos (c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] 517 BC), conquered Thrace, waged war on Scythia (c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] 512 BC), and suppressed rebellions started in 500 BC, leading to the Battle of Lade (494 BC).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The navy had lost its presence in the Aegean Sea, and its strength was reduced.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] 468 BC), the Persians were defeated and lost 200 ships according to the account of Thucydides.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The next significant defeat occurred in c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] 450 BC, when they lost a war in Cyprus (near modern-day Larnaca).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The creation the organization, infrastructure, and financial basis of the Achaemenid navy is attributed to Darius I.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The coasts of Phoenicia, as well as Cyprus and Cilicia, always played a strategic role in the Achaemenid navy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Strabo and Herodotus mentioned two central bases for the navy: one in Cilicia and the other in Kyme–Phocaea (both located in modern-day Turkey).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Centers that trained crew for vessels were isolated from the central bases.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The Cilician base was heavily guarded by a large number of troops, whose payments were financed by the local tributes in that satrapy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] It is likely that Acco served as the third main base.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] According to Kaveh Farrokh, the first naval headquarters that hosted high command of the navy was located along the Shatt al-Arab, where it leads to the Persian Gulf (located in the modern-day Khuzestan Province of Iran).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] However, Cilicia was the main base and was always ready for deployment because unlike Shatt al-Arab, it was intended for power projection.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Smaller squadrons were stationed elsewhere, like those of Sidon and Halicarnassus, as well as Samos.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] An important base was a shipyard located at Tripolis, where Lebanese timber were nearby.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The Nile valley also served as a strategic base of operation, when Egypt was a satrapy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Achaemenid settlements like Bahrain, Oman, Yemen and the Indian subcontinent were regular destinations for naval ships.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] It is thought likely that bases existed in Abdera and Myus, though this is uncertain.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The naval forces had an active presence in the Black Sea, the Aegean Sea, the Mediterranean Sea and the Persian Gulf among others.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] They operated patrols in river or littoral environments like Shatt al-Arab and Euphrates in Mesopotamia, Nile in Egypt and Sind in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The command hierarchy of the navy is not certain, but Greek sources indicate that high commanders were selected from the imperial aristocracy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] There are reports of commanders of ships, and commanding officers of fleets with various non-Persians backgrounds, such as those of Carians.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Commanders of Greek origin are also reported to have served in the navy, including even one Athenian.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Almost nothing is known about sailors of lower rank.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] In the wake of creating the navy, Persians hired Phoenician rowers and sailors, but later recruited from other subject peoples.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The marines standing in the forces were either Persians, Medes, or Scythians.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The servicemen were probably employed with full payment, because lengthy deployments imposed a drastic change to their communities especially if it included one or two harvests.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The first Achaemenid naval vessels, which were built at Phoenician shipyards, measured 40 meters (130 ft) in length and 6 meters (20 ft) width, and were capable of carrying 300 troops at best.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] According to Christopher Tuplin, Cypriot ships "appear a significant element in Persian fleets on various occasions".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The Persians were the first nation to use triremes in significant numbers.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The first large trireme was commissioned by Cambyses.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] By 490 BC, the backbone of the fleet was consisted of triremes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Some triremes were modified as troopers, as well as some for carrying horses and supplies or building bridges.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Persian triremes differed from those of the Greek, and used Phoenician design.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The third level of rowers in Greek vessels was accommodated by adding a outrigger, but the Persians added to the height of the compartment instead.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] They reportedly were 110 feet (34 m) to 120 feet (37 m) long and had a beam of 15 feet (4.6 m).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The ships were most likely capable of reaching 12 knots (22 km/h) under good sailing conditions.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] They could reach full speed in 30 seconds from a dead stop.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Equipped with one mast with square sail, the triremes had rudders made up of two bladed oars, one on each side of stern, united by a crossbar.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The ram was made out of bronze, and was long and tapered to a single point.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The metal rams were designed to slice into the hulls of enemy ships after an impact.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Equipment included grappling hooks (used to catch and halt enemy ships) and two mangonels, the latter throwing stones or flammable projectiles.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] A typical Persian trireme is reported to have had 170 rowers, with the upper file carrying 62, and the middle and lower files each 54.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] In addition to the rowers, other personnel aboard triremes included 14 marines and some spare rowers and oars in case they were needed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] In 480 BC, each trireme carried 200 men and 30 marines, according to Herodotus.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Triremes were too crowded to store their own supplies, and relied on support vessels for food and water.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] It was normal for the crew to disembark in the evening for eating and sleep.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Achaemenid navy later used more advanced vessels like quinqueremes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Other types of vessel in the fleet were triaconters, penteconters and light boats.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Smaller vessels used for river patrols could carry a maximum of 100–200 troops.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The navy operated a large number of vessels used to carry food and other supplies, which commonly had a displacement of 100 to 150 tons, at the time they invaded Egypt in 373 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Ships capable of carrying 350 to 500 tons were also used in significant numbers.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] They also had horse transporters (*hippagogoi*) specifically built for this purpose, that could easily carry 30 horses.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Persian horse transport ships were good sailing ships that took advantage of the favorable winds, according to Anthony J.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Papalas, who adds they were probably designed to match the speed of a trireme.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] It is probable that horse transports were galleys with a shallow draft, that allowed horses get off in the waters and embark via a ramp.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The Achaemenids are known to have used vessels for connecting the banks of rivers.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The bridges were built by joining vessels to one another and lashing them together, to erect a roadway with planks.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Xenophon reports such bridges, one made using 37 boats on Tigris, and another using seven on Maeander.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] During its early years under Cambyses, the Achaemenid navy is assumed to possess about 300 triremes, which was equal to the sum of the fleet of Egypt and its ally Polycrates of Samos.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] This number was later doubled, with 600 triremes mentioned in 494 and 490 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The initial set-up of the navy (300 triremes) may have had up to 51,000 rowers and thousands of sailors and marines.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The original number of vessels in the fleet was eventually quadrupled, according to Greek sources.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Herodotus' account of naval forces under Xerxes I, put the number of warships in service at 1,207, in addition to 3,000 transport ships.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Contemporary academic estimates range from 500 to 1,000 vessels, according to Matt Waters.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Scholars maintain that this number included large numbers of reserve ships, and the navy had not enough full oar crews to operate them all.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Herodotus also states that Persians arrived for the Battle of Marathon (490 BC) with 600 triremes and some horse transport vessels.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Though the number is rejected by some academics, Anthony J.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Papalas states that evidence does support this report.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Considering that each ship had an average of 50 oarsmen (the absolute minimum for a trireme) and 10 to 20 seamen and marines were also aboard, the navy compromised 36,000 to 42,000 men, at least.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] After the Battle of Salamis (480 BC), the fleet began to decline and never regained its peak numbers.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The largest figure estimated after 404 BC is 400 triremes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The number was still equal to, if not more than, the fleets of the Athenian alliance.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Xenophon wrote in *Anabasis*, "his (Cyrus the Younger) ensign was a golden eagle with outspread wings mounted upon a long shaft and this continues even unto this day as the ensign of the Persian king".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] While there is not much to confirm this, some scholars maintain that *Alexander Mosaic* contained a depiction of the standard (on the part which is now damaged), head of a bird in yellow on a red cloth.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] There is also a square plaque found at Apadana in plain, and it is quite possible that it shows the eagle.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The Achaemenid navy was the first true "imperial navy" that appeared in history.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] Persians are also credited for establishing the 'trireme navy' as the naval standard of their time.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The establishment of the Achaemenid navy set the basis of Iranian naval engineering, as well as "a powerful Persian maritime tradition that remained in the region until the arrival of the British East India Company and the Royal Navy by the mid-19th century AD".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The naval forces affected the coastal subjects of the Achaemenid Empire to a great extent.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] They were put under much tighter control from the capital, and were heavily involved in military campaigns of the Achaemenids.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/achaemenid-navy] The Sidonians profited financially from the naval base stationed in their city.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] Actium belonged originally to the Corinthian colonists of Anactorium, who probably founded the sanctuary of Apollo Actius.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] In the 3rd century BC it fell to the Acarnanians, who subsequently held their religious summits there.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] There was also an ancient festival named Actia, celebrated here in honour of the god.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] Augustus after his victory enlarged the temple, and revived the ancient festival, which was henceforth celebrated once in five years (πενταετηρίς, ludi quinquennales), with musical and gymnastic contests, and horse races.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] We learn from a Greek inscription found on the site of Actium, and which is probably prior to the time of Augustus, that the chief priest of the temple was called Ἱεραπόλος, and that his name was employed in official documents, like that of the first Archon at Athens, to mark the date.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] Strabo says that the temple was situated on an eminence, and that below was a plain with a grove of trees, and a dock-yard; and in another passage he describes the harbour as situated outside of the gulf.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] On the opposite coast of Epirus, Augustus founded the city of Nicopolis in honour of his victory.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] After the foundation of Nicopolis, a few buildings sprang up around the temple, and it served as a kind of suburb to Nicopolis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] On October 8, 1980, the Greek Ministry of Transport and Communications reported that shipwrecks from the Battle of Actium had been located at Actium near the entrance to the Ambracan Gulf.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] In Summer 2009, archaeologists discovered the ruins of the Temple of Apollo and found two statue heads, one of Apollo, one of Artemis (Diana).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] The peninsula is connected via an underwater tunnel to the city of Preveza in Epirus, on the opposite side of the mouth of the Ambracian Gulf.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/actium] The total length of the tunnel is 1,570 metres (5,150 ft), of which 909 metres (2,982 ft) are located underwater.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 2026 Aden had a population estimated at 1,194,160, making it one of the largest cities in Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] It is the capital and principal part of Aden Governorate, encompassing eight districts.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] During the colonial period, the name *Aden* referred to the area along the north coast of the gulf, encompassing Tawahi, Mualla, Crater, and much of Khor Maksar district.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The western harbour peninsula, known as *Little Aden*, now falls within the Al Buraiqeh district.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The city and surrounding area were under British administration from 1839 until independence in 1967.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Before gaining independence, Aden comprised distinct sectors: Crater, the original port; Ma'alla, the modern port; Tawahi, formerly "Steamer Point"; and Gold Mohur resorts.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Khormaksar, on the isthmus connecting Aden to the mainland, hosts diplomatic missions, Aden University's main offices, and Aden International Airport.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aden encloses the eastern side of a vast natural harbour that constitutes the modern port.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Little Aden was developed as the site of the oil refinery and tanker port.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Both were established and operated by British Petroleum until they were turned over to South Yemeni government ownership and control in 1978.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aden used to be the capital of South Yemen until its union with North Yemen on 22 May 1990.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] It has been the temporary capital of Yemen since the start of the Yemeni civil war, hosting some members of the Cabinet of Yemen mainly in al-Maashiq Palace.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] It was also the seat of the secessionist Southern Transitional Council from 2018 to 2026.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aden is a home and a place for ships, and in Arabic the word "Aden" means residence, and it is said "Aden Al-Balad", meaning the settlement of the country.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Yaqut al-Hamwi said: "It is a famous city on the coast of the Indian Sea, towards the Yemen, and it is poor, with no water or pasture.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Ibn Khaldun said: "This Aden is one of the most fortified cities in Yemen, and it is on the bank of the Indian Sea.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aden is an ancient port and was mentioned by the Greeks under the name (Ancient Greek: Αραβία Εμπόριον, romanised: *Arabia Emporion*), which means an Arabic trade port.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The port's convenient position on the sea route between India and Europe has made Aden desirable to rulers who sought to possess it at various times throughout history.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The same work describes Aden as "a village by the shore", which would well describe the town of Crater while it was still little developed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] There is no mention of fortification at this stage.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aden was more an island than a peninsula, as the isthmus (a tombolo) was not then so developed as it is today.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] At its beginning, the city was a small peninsula with no significant natural resources, but its location between Egypt and India made it important in the ancient Indian Ocean trade route.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The city was the home of the ancient Kingdom of Awsan from the eighth to seventh centuries BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In the second half of the first century BC, the Roman Emperor Augustus Caesar determined to control Arabia Felix and reach the Indian Ocean.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aelius Gallus' Roman expedition to Arabia Felix (26–25 BCE) aimed to capture the Sabaean capital of Marib but failed due to extreme desert conditions, disease, and logistical challenges.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] After an unsuccessful week-long siege, the army, weakened by illness and dehydration, withdrew, losing most of its ~10,000 troops to environmental factors and disease" The Himyarites overthrew the Kingdom of Sheba in 275 AD and took control of Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Recent incomplete archaeological studies suggest that the Himyarites were the ones who built the huge water cisterns currently known as the "Cisterns of Aden", which stored approximately 136,382,757 litres of water.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Himyarite Kingdom fell in the first quarter of the sixth century AD.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Yusuf Dhu Nuwas mentioned Bab al-Mandab in one of his writings.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The forces of the Kingdom of Aksum were entering Yemen through it.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Byzantine Emperor Justinian I sent a fleet to fight the Himyarite Jews and support the Kingdom of Aksum and the Christians of Najran.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Byzantine sources indicate that the Sasanian Empire took control of the city in 571 AD.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] A local legend in Yemen states that Aden may be as old as human history itself.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Some also believe that Cain and Abel are buried somewhere in the city.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Although the pre-Islamic Himyar civilisation was capable of building large structures, there seems to have been little fortification at this stage.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Fortifications at Mareb and other places in Yemen and the Hadhramaut make it clear that both the Himyar and the Sabean cultures were well capable of it.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Thus, watchtowers, since destroyed, are possible.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] However, the Arab historians Ibn al Mujawir and Abu Makhramah attribute the first fortification of Aden to Beni Zuree'a.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Abu Makhramah has also included a detailed biography of Muhammad Azim Sultan Qamarbandi Naqsh in his work, Tarikh ul-Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The aim seems to have been twofold: to keep hostile forces out and to maintain revenue by controlling the movement of goods, thereby preventing smuggling.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In its original form, some of this work was relatively feeble.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] With the introduction of Islam to Yemen in the seventh century AD, Aden experienced a period of stagnation that lasted until the ninth century AD.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In the early years of Islam, Aden belonged to the province of Jund (Taiz).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] It was controlled by the state of Ziyadid and the Sulayhid.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] After the death of Ali bin Muhammad Al-Sulayhi, his son took charge of Zurayids, and Aden continued to pay the annual royalty until Queen Arwa bint Ahmed Al-Sulayhi reduced it.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] After the fall of the Sulayhid state, the Banu Zurayi became independent in Aden, taking advantage of the Sulayhids' preoccupation with the Khawlan tribes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Zurayites continued to rule Aden, Lahj, and Abyan for less than forty years until they fell under the Ayyubids' control of the city.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] A major battle took place between Turan Shah bin Ayyub and Yasser bin Bilal al-Muhammadi, Minister of State, and the Zurayiyyah were defeated and al-Muhammadi fled to Taiz.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] One of the most important contributors to the defeat of the Zurayids was their ongoing wars with the Bani Mahdi in Tihama and the departure of their army to confront the Ayyubids instead of fortifying themselves in Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] After 1175, rebuilding in a more solid form began, and ever since then Aden has been a popular city attracting sailors and merchants from Egypt, Sindh, Gujarat, East Africa and even China.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] According to Muqaddasi, Persians formed the majority of Aden's population in the 10th century.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] During the Ayyubid period in Yemen, Sanaa and its environs were more hostile to their presence than other regions.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Zaidi tribes were able to defeat the Ayyubids in 1226, but Omar bin Rasul, the founder of the Rasulid state, was able to repel them, so he tightened his control over Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The city regained its position during the days of the Rasulids, so they dug wells and built schools, and Aden flourished commercially.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The kings of Bani Rasul were also merchants and enacted a number of laws and regulations to codify trade in the city.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Banu Tahir were able to control Aden after the Banu Rasool, and the Italian traveller Lodovico di Verthama describes it as one of the most powerful cities seen on Earth during the days of the Tahirids.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 1513, the Portuguese, led by Afonso de Albuquerque, launched an unsuccessful four-day naval siege of Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Mamluks in Egypt sensed the danger and sent a force led by Hussein al-Kurdi.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The victorious King Amer bin Abdul Wahhab provided great aid to the Kurds, but he suffered a heavy defeat in the Battle of Diu.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Mamluks sent a second fleet, but the victorious king refused to cooperate with the Mamluks because he had succeeded in repelling the Portuguese from Aden without their help.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Hussein al-Kurdi became angry and allied with the Zaidi Imam, who was opposed to the Tahirids, al-Mutawakkil Sharaf al-Din, and the Tahirid cities fell successively, with the exception of Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Ottoman Empire took control of the city in 1538.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Ottomans' goal was to prevent the Portuguese from controlling Aden, so the city witnessed difficult days, in addition to the fact that the port of Mocha gained greater importance at the expense of Aden during the sixteenth century.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The city's population declined and it turned into a small village with a population of no more than 600 people.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] While its population was approximately eighty thousand people during the days of the Rasulid state.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 1421, China's Ming dynasty Yongle Emperor ordered principal envoy grand eunuch Li Xing and grand eunuch Zhou Man of Zheng He's fleet to convey an imperial edict with hats and robes to bestow on the king of Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The envoys boarded three treasure ships and set sail from Sumatra to the port of Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] This event was recorded in the book *Yingyai Shenglan* by Ma Huan who accompanied the imperial envoy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] After Ottoman rule, Aden was ruled by the Sultanate of Lahej, under suzerainty of the Zaidi imams of Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The first political intercourse between Lahej and the British took place in 1799, when a naval force was sent from Great Britain, with a detachment of troops from India, to occupy the island of Perim and prevent all communication of the French in Egypt with the Indian Ocean, by way of the Red Sea.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The island of Perim was found unsuitable for troops, and the Sultan of Lahej, Ahmed bin Abdul Karim, received the detachment for some time at Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] He proposed to enter into an alliance and to grant Aden as a permanent station, but the offer was declined.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] A Treaty was, however, concluded with the Sultan in 1802 by Admiral Sir Home Popham, who was instructed to enter into political and commercial alliances with the chief rulers on the Arabian coast of the Red Sea.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The imams relied on the revenues from the port of Mocha, and Aden was not as important as the Abadlahs were.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] At the end of the eighteenth century, Sultan *Fadl al-Abdali* concluded an alliance with the Yafi tribes to rebel against the Zaidi imams and monopolise Aden's revenues equally among them.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Sultan of Lahej got rid of the imams, but he did not fulfil his promise to Yafa.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Zaidi imams did not recognise inheritance and saw fighting for the imamate, so the war between *Al-Nasir Muhammad bin Ishaq* and *Al-Mansur Al-Hussein bin Al-Mutawakkil* prolonged, so Al-Abdali took the opportunity to declare his independence in Lahej and Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The English had been visiting Aden and Mocha from 1609, led by Sir Henry Middleton, who was imprisoned, his ships confiscated, and eight of his men killed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The British tried to conclude treaties with the Zaidi imams after the Ottomans were expelled from Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] They visited Sanaa and Mocha, but they treated the British ambassador poorly and rejected his offer.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Things were different when the Abdali gained independence from Lahj and Medina.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] They signed a treaty with the British in 1802, stipulating that they build a factory in Crater and allocate a special cemetery for British subjects free of charge.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Abdali wanted protection from the tribes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Sultan Fadl bin Ali was killed by Yafi' gunmen, then one of the sheikhs of Al-Hujariya invaded Lahj and besieged it for five months.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Al-Awaliq also besieged it with eight thousand fighters, and they did not leave until Sultan Ahmed bin Abdul Karim paid them seven thousand dollars.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Then the Fadl family attacked Aden in 1836.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 1609 *The Ascension* was the first English ship to visit Aden, before sailing on to Mocha during the fourth voyage of the East India Company.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] British interests in Aden began in 1796 with Napoleon's invasion of Egypt, after which a British fleet docked at Aden for several months at the invitation of the sultan.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The French were defeated in Egypt in 1801, and their privateers were tracked down over the subsequent decade.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] By 1800, Aden was a small village with a population of 600 Arabs, Somalis, Jews, and Indians—housed for the most part in huts of reed matting erected among ruins recalling a vanished era of wealth and prosperity.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] As there was little British trade in the Red Sea, most British politicians until the 1830s had no further interest in the area beyond the suppression of piracy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] However, a small number of government officials and the East India Company officials thought that a British base in the area was necessary to prevent another French advance through Egypt or Russian expansion through Persia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The emergence of Muhammad Ali of Egypt as a strong local ruler only increased their concerns.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The governor of Bombay from 1834 to 1838, Sir Robert Grant, was one of those who believed that India could only be protected by preemptively seizing "places of strength" to protect the Indian Ocean.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Red Sea increased in importance after the steamship *Hugh Lindsay* sailed from Bombay to the Suez isthmus in 1830, stopping at Aden with the sultan's consent to resupply with coal.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Although cargo was still carried around the Cape of Good Hope in sailing ships, a steam route to the Suez could provide a much quicker option for transporting officials and important communications.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Grant felt that armed ships steaming regularly between Bombay and Suez would help secure British interests in the region and did all he could to progress his vision.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] After lengthy negotiations due to the costs of investing in the new technology, the government agreed to pay half the costs for six voyages per year and the East India Company board approved the purchase of two new steamers in 1837.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Grant immediately announced that monthly voyages to Suez would take place, despite the fact that no secure coal supplying station had been found.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The British first stationed a coal depot on the island of Socotra in 1834.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] However, due to the lack of suitable infrastructure there, they quickly lost interest in Socotra and turned towards Aden instead.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 1838, under Muhsin bin Fadl, Lahej ceded 194 km2 (75 sq mi) including Aden to the British.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On 19 January 1839, the British East India Company landed Royal Marines at Aden to definitively conquer the territory (the so-called Aden Expedition) and stop attacks by pirates against British shipping to India.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 1850 it was declared a free trade port, with the liquor, salt, arms, and opium trades developing duties as it won all the coffee trade from Mokha.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The port lies about equidistant from the Suez Canal, Bombay, and Zanzibar, which were all important British possessions.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aden had been an entrepôt and a way-station for ships in the ancient world.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] There, supplies, particularly water, were replenished, so, in the mid-19th century, it became necessary to replenish coal and boiler water.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Thus Aden acquired a coaling station at Steamer Point and Aden was to remain under British control until November 1967.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Until 1937, Aden was governed as part of British India and was known as the Aden Settlement.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Its original territory was enlarged in 1857 by the 13 km2 (5.0 sq mi) island of Perim, in 1868 by the 73 km2 (28 sq mi) Khuriya Muriya Islands, and in 1915 by the 108 km2 (42 sq mi) island of Kamaran.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The settlement would become Aden Province in 1935.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 1937, the settlement was detached from India and became the Colony of Aden, a British Crown colony.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The change in government was a step towards the change in the official currency unit.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] When British India became independent in 1947, Indian rupees (divided into annas) were replaced in Aden by East African shillings.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The hinterland of Aden and Hadhramaut were also loosely tied to Britain as the Aden Protectorate, which was overseen from Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aden's location also made it a useful *entrepôt* for mail passing between places around the Indian Ocean and Europe.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Thus, a ship passing from Suez to Bombay could leave mail for Mombasa at Aden for collection (See *Postage stamps and postal history of Aden*).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In December 1947, a three-day riot broke out in reaction to the drafting of the Partition Plan for Palestine.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The riots and their repression by the Aden Protectorate Levies saw the killing of 76–82 Jews, 33 Arabs, 4 Muslim Indians and 1 Somali, in addition to looting and damaging of property.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] After the Suez Crisis in 1956, the British held on to Aden as an outpost in the region for another decade.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The British authorities had already decided to further expand its port shortly before the Suez Canal's 1956 closure.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aden sent a team of two to the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games in Perth, Western Australia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In order to stabilise Aden and the surrounding Aden Protectorate from the designs of the Egyptian backed republicans of North Yemen, the British attempted gradually to unite the disparate states of the region in preparation for eventual independence.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On 18 January 1963, the Colony of Aden was incorporated into the Federation of Arab Emirates of the South against the wishes of North Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The city became the State of Aden and the Federation was renamed the Federation of South Arabia (FSA).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] An insurgency against British administration known as the Aden Emergency began with a grenade attack by the communist National Liberation Front (NLF), against the British High Commissioner on 10 December 1963, killing one person and injuring fifty, and a "state of emergency" was declared.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 1964, Britain announced its intention to grant independence to the FSA in 1968, but that British troops would remain in Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The security situation deteriorated as NLF and FLOSY (Front for the Liberation of Occupied South Yemen) vied for the upper hand.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In January 1967, there were mass riots between the NLF and their rival FLOSY supporters in the old Arab quarter of Aden town.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] This conflict continued until mid February, despite the intervention of British troops.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On 20 June 1967, 23 British Army soldiers were ambushed and shot dead by members of Aden Police during the Aden Mutiny in the Crater District.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] During the period there were as many attacks on the British troops by both sides as against each other, culminating in the destruction of an Aden Airways DC3 plane in the air with no survivors.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The increased violence was a determining factor in the British ensuring all families were evacuated more quickly than initially intended, as recorded in *From Barren Rocks to Living Stones*.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On 30 November 1967, British troops were evacuated, leaving Aden and the rest of the FSA under NLF control.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Royal Marines, who had been the first British troops to arrive in Aden in 1839, were almost the last to leave, followed only by the 10 Airfields Squadron of the Royal Engineers, which left Aden on 13 December 1967.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Helicopters of aircraft carrier HMS *Albion* (R07), part of a Royal Navy task force, lifted off the Royal Marine commandos who had been left to secure the airfield.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Qahtan al-Sha'bi assumed the presidency of the new state, and the sheikhdoms of the Eastern Protectorate of Hadramaut and Al-Mahra were annexed to the new state.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Al-Shaabi took over a new country with a collapsed economy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Civilian workers and businessmen left, and British support ceased.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The closure of the Suez Canal in 1967 played an important role in the country's economy, as it reduced the number of ships crossing Aden by 75%.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The new state was divided into six governorates on 11 December 1967, in order to end the manifestations of tribalism in the state and ignore the tribal borders between the defunct sheikhdoms.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On March 20, 1968, Qahtan dismissed all leftist leaders from the government and party membership.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] He was able to put down a rebellion led by leftist factions in the army in May of the same year, and faced new rebellions from leftist parties in July, August and December 1968.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] This is because all Arab countries welcomed the front.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] National Liberation received a cold reception.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Regimes like Egypt wanted to merge the National Front with the Front for the Liberation of Occupied South Yemen, where the leftist section was more numerous than the supporters of the popular Qahtan.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] They wanted a regime that would lead the masses and face the great challenges facing the new state, the most important of which was the bankruptcy of the treasury.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Qahtan al-Shaabi dismissed Interior Minister Muhammad Ali Haitham on 16 June 1969, but the latter, with his ties to the tribes and the army, reassembled the leftist forces that had been dispersed by President Qahtan al-Shaabi, and they were able to place him under house arrest on 22 June.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] A presidential committee was formed from Five people: Salem Rabie Ali, who became president, Muhammad Saleh Al-Awlaki, Ali Antar, Abdel Fattah Ismail, and Muhammad Ali Haitham, who became prime minister.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] This group took an extreme leftist line, declaring its support for the Palestinians and the Dhofar Revolution, and strengthening its relationship with the Soviet Union.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] West Germany severed its relationship with the state due to its recognition of East Germany, and the United States also severed its relationship in October 1969.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The new powers issued a new constitution, nationalised foreign banks and insurance companies, and changed the name of the country to the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen in line with the Marxist–Leninist approach they followed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] A centrally planned economy was established.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The port of Aden was the largest source of national income for the Republic of South Yemen, but the closure of the Suez Canal by Egypt between 1967 and 1975 – reduced commercial activities in the port.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Salem Rubaya Ali wanted to adopt a practical approach, so he communicated with the President of North Yemen, Ibrahim al-Hamdi, and made attempts to restore normal relations with Western countries.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] During his presidency, relations between South Yemen and Saudi Arabia were established in 1976.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] President Salmin, as he is known, coveted more Soviet support, so the contract with Saudi Arabia worried him.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Soviets pushed them to increase aid, but relations with Saudi Arabia became strained again in 1977 following the assassination of North Yemeni President Ibrahim al-Hamdi.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] It is believed that Salem Rabie Ali orchestrated the assassination of Ahmed Hussein al-Ghashmi in revenge for Ibrahim al-Hamdi.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Salem Rabie Ali was subjected to a quick trial that ended with his execution and Abdel Fattah Ismail assuming the presidency of South Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Relations with North Yemen became tense, due to Fattah's support for the factions opposing Ali Abdullah Saleh, who was more fanatical than his predecessors.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Relations with the Soviet Union became active in an unprecedented way, so the Front War broke out in 1978, in which the Soviet Union and the United States intervened.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Ali Nasser Muhammad was able to force Abd al-Fattah Ismail al-Jawfi to resign for "health reasons", and Ismail was exiled to Moscow two years after he assumed the presidency.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Despite the approach of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen and its removal of tribal aspects, tribalism remained alive among politicians and the public despite the exposure of its sheikhs.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Tribal and regional favouritism and nepotism remained rife in southern Yemen, as political forces called on their tribal and regional affiliations during crises.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] By January 1986, Aden was torn apart by the rivalry of two factions in the ruling Socialist Party, when President Ali Nasser Muhammad's guards launched a surprise attack on the political party's office in Aden on 13 January 1986.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] This was the beginning of the 1986 civil war in South Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Ali Nasser Muhammad was from Abyan Governorate, while most of those killed in the political party office were from Al-Dhalea and Lahj.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Military brigades from those areas bombed Aden from land and sea, forcing Ali Nasser Muhammad to flee and hundreds of thousands of civilians and soldiers to flee to northern Yemen, including Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] This was followed by systematic killings and liquidations against the people of Abyan Governorate, on charges that they were collaborating with Ali Nasser Muhammad.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Nearly ten thousand people were killed, and thousands migrated towards North Yemen, most of whom were from Abyan and Shabwa.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] With the unification of north and south Yemen in 1990, Aden was no longer a national capital but remained the capital of *Aden Governorate* which covered an area similar to that of the Aden Colony.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On 29 December 1992, Al Qaeda conducted its first known terrorist attack in Aden, bombing the Gold Mohur Hotel, where US servicemen were known to have been staying en route to Somalia for Operation Restore Hope.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] A Yemeni and an Austrian tourist died in the attack.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] That war marked the end of the state of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen, and Haider Abu Bakr Al-Attas assumed the presidency until May 22, 1990, the unity of South Yemen with North Yemen, and the establishment of the Republic of Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] At that time, Ali Salem al-Beidh was considered Ali Abdullah Saleh's deputy, and Haider Abu Bakr Al-Attas was considered prime minister, and after the 1993 elections.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Conflicts began within the ruling coalition, and Vice President Ali Salem Al-Beidh retreated to Aden in August 1993.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The general security situation in the country deteriorated, and the complete integration of the two armies failed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The southern forces, which were transferred to Amran, clashed with the northern forces there, and the forces of the northern giants, which were transferred to Amran, clashed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] At the forefront of these emerged a group of the brightest officers, such as Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi, who became Minister of Defense at the time; the former Chief of Staff, Major General Abdullah Aliwa; and Major General Salem Qatan, who was assassinated by an Al-Qaeda gunman.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] After the war, Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi was appointed Vice President of the Republic, and remained in office.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] He held his position until 2012, when he was elected president of the country.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Members of al Qaeda attempted to bomb the US guided-missile destroyer *The Sullivans* at the port of Aden as part of the 2000 millennium attack plots.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The boat that had the explosives in it sank, forcing the planned attack to be aborted.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The bombing attack on destroyer USS *Cole* took place in Aden on 12 October 2000.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 2007 growing dissatisfaction with unification led to the formation of the secessionist South Yemen Movement.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] According to *The New York Times*, the Movement's mainly underground leadership includes socialists, Islamists and individuals desiring a return to the perceived benefits of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aden remained in a state of political stagnation for 25 years until President Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi took refuge there and carried out his work from the Republican Palace in Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On 7 March 2015, Hadi declared Aden the temporary capital, instead of Sanaa, which he described as occupied by the Houthis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] This was after the Houthis took control of Sanaa on 21 September 2014, and imposed a siege on the Republican Palace and the home of President Hadi on 20 January.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On 22 January, Hadi submitted his resignation to Parliament; it did not hold a session to accept or reject the resignation, and Hadi remained under house arrest imposed by the Houthis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] President Abd Rabbuh Mansur Hadi fled to Aden, his hometown, in February 2015 after being deposed in the coup d'état that many consider to be the start of the Yemeni civil war.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Others consider that the civil war began in September 2014 when Houthi forces took over the capital city Sanaa, which was followed by a rapid Houthi takeover of the government.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Hadi declared in Aden that he was still Yemen's legitimate president and called on state institutions and loyal officials to relocate to Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In a televised speech on 21 March 2015, he declared Aden to be Yemen's "economic and temporary capital" while Sanaa is controlled by the Houthis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aden was hit by violence in the aftermath of the coup d'état, with forces loyal to Hadi clashing with those loyal to former president Ali Abdullah Saleh in a battle for Aden International Airport on 19 March 2015.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] After the airport battle, the entire city became a battleground for the Battle of Aden, which left large parts of the city in ruins and has killed at least 198 people since 25 March 2015.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Some Arab and foreign embassies were transferred to Aden, and Defense Minister Mahmoud Al-Subaihi was able to leave Sanaa for Aden and met with President Hadi.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On March 4, 2016, unidentified gunmen stormed the Mother Teresa House in the city and killed sixteen people, including four nuns.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] A number of the old city's churches have also been destroyed by Islamic extremists since mid-2015.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On 14 July 2015, the Saudi Arabian Army launched an offensive to win control of the city.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Within three days, the city was cleared of Houthi rebels, ending the Battle of Aden with a coalition victory.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Beginning on 28 January 2018, separatists loyal to the Southern Transitional Council (STC) seized control of the Yemeni government headquarters in Aden in a coup d'état against the Hadi-led government.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Prime Minister Maeen Abdulmalik Saeed, his ministers and his entourage were conducted to safety under the barrage of hostile fire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On 7 January 2026, the Yemeni government forces managed to control Aden following the collapse of the Southern Transitional Council.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The entry of the Yemenis into Islam contributed to their abandoning their ancient script and replacing it with the late Nabataean alphabet in which the Qur'an was written.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Today, Yemenis speak Arabic in the Yemeni dialect, which is a developed dialect and closely linked to the ancient language.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] It has three dialects with branches: the Sanʽani dialect, the Hadrami dialect, and the Taʽizzi-Adeni dialect, in addition to the Bedouin dialect of the residents of Marib.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Al Jawf, Shabwa, and Inner Hadhramaut, and each of these dialects has characteristics and features.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Adeni art or the *Adeniyat* is an art of Arabic music.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Among the ancient artists of Aden are Iskander Thabet Saleh and Muhammad Murshid Naji, and among the poets are Abdul Rahman Ibrahim Muhammad, Ahmed Ghaleb Muhammad Al-Jabri, Abdullah Abdul Karim Muhammad, Ali Abdullah Jaafar Aman, Farid Muhammad Barakat, Lotfi Jaafar Aman, and Mohsen Ali Brik.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] "Adeni music" played a major role in Aden society, and artists in the Aden dialect were called "al-Mutariba", meaning people of music.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Adeni music began in 1920 when the army of the Aden Protectorate was formed, and after it the National Guard, where there were teams for those forces and those teams participated On special occasions and weddings.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The city of Aden is considered the first city in which sports were practiced in the Arabian Peninsula, and the first private club in Aden was founded in 1905 under the name "Al-Ittihad Al-Muhammadi Club", as the first sports club in Yemen and the Arab world.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] He was fighting the occupation army divisions and the fleet divisions coming and passing to the port of Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 1924, the "Al-Husseini Sports Club" was founded in Crater, and a third club appeared in Tawahi under the name "Al-Bamboot Club" and Sheikh Othman.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The 1930s witnessed the emergence of a number of clubs.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 1933, the "Nujoom Al-Layl Club", Al-Aidrousi Club, and Nujoom Al-Sabah Club appeared in Crater, and in Tawahi, the "Al-Ittihad Al-Islami Club" (Al-Mawlada) appeared.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Until that year, football matches were played in a friendly manner between the teams of the Crater, Al-Tawahi, and Sheikh Othman regions, as there were no federations regulating sports activity.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 1934, the occupation authority announced the establishment of a sports association called the "Adeniya Sports Association", after the increasing number of local clubs.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Its members were appointed by the Governor-General of Aden, and all of its members were English, headed by the English Governor of Aden, Bernard Reilly, as sponsor.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The association's board of directors consists of Hikam Bottom as president, the Indian Rosario as secretary, and two other members.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] This association began holding the first club tournament, which was the "Rosario Cup Championship".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Among the most important tournaments held in Aden before independence were the Rosario Cup, the Riley Cup, the Somali Bassem Al-Nar Cup, the Aramco Cup, and the Kik Muncherji Championship.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] After independence, the "Football Federation" was established on January 18, 1968, on the ruins of the "Adeniya Sports Association".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] The Federation took a decision regarding the Adeniya clubs, which had numbered about 64 sports clubs, reducing and merging the clubs in Aden and Lahj to only 16 clubs, and the clubs were forced to join or unite with large teams.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In February 1968, several sports clubs were abolished, leaving only 12 clubs remaining.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In December 1968, Al-Islah Club and Al-Shaab Club were merged into one club under the name of the latter in Al-Tawahi.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In 1969, the Al-Ittihad Al-Muhammadi Club and Al-Tadamon Club were united in Crater, under the name Al-Tadamon Al-Muhammadi Club.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In the "First General Sports Conference" in 1973, the clubs were merged and reduced again, so that their number became only 7 clubs: Al-Ahrar Club, Al-Ahly Club, Shamsan Club, Al-Shaab Club, Al-Hilal Club, United Youth Club, and Aden Tennis Club.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On July 18, 1975, the stage of forming urban clubs, and the beginning of the stage of politicisation of the clubs in favour of the National Liberation Front, took place.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] It was decided to change their names and reduce them to become 5 clubs: Al-Tilal Club, Shamsan Club, Al-Minaa Club, Al-Wahda Club, and Al-Shoula Club.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] On July 18, 1975, the "Al-Tilal Sports Club" appeared, headed by Yassin Saeed Noman, as a new name for the "Al-Ittihad Al-Muhammadi Club", which was founded in 1905, and in 1976 the "Yemeni Football Federation" appeared.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Football is the most popular sport in Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] There are 9 stadiums in Aden, including the May 22 International Stadium, and 10 sports clubs.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] In November 2010, Aden hosted the 2010 Arabian Gulf Football Cup.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p01] Aden has several historical and natural sites of interest to visitors.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The industrial activity in Aden is represented by a group of factories and production units, the forefront of which is the oil refinery.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The oil refinery in Aden is considered one of the first refineries to be established in the region, and began operating in 1954 AD.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The Aden Refineries Company has facilities such as an oil tanker port, a network of storage tanks, and a centre to supply ships with fuel.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Historically, Aden was a station for importing goods from the African coast and from Europe, the United States, and India.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] As of 1920, Aden was a major commercial centre for trade in the Arabian Peninsula, and the port exported small quantities of local products to most Arab ports.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Aden provided coal and salt to passing ships, and the port was a stopping point for ships when they entered Bab al-Mandab.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Historically, the port of Aden was the main transport port in the region.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Passenger ships land in Al-Tawahi District, and the city is served by Aden International Airport, which is about 10 kilometres (6 mi) from the city.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The airport is the main headquarters of Al-Saeeda Airlines and its operations centre.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The airport is considered the second largest airport.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] In Yemen, after Sanaa International Airport, it is considered the best airport in Yemen in terms of location due to the mountainous nature of Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] However, this airport is surrounded by the Arabian Sea in terms of take-off and landing.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The establishment of Aden Airport dates back to the year 1927 when the British forces established a military airport in the district.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] After World War II, Britain carried out extensive urban modernisation and built Aden International Airport, known today, next to the military airport.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Alyemda Airlines was the official carrier of South Yemen, before unification, and was based in Aden, before merging with Yemen Airways in 1996.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Before the Battle of Aden Airport and the 2015 military intervention in Yemen closed this airport along with other airports in Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] On 22 July, Aden International Airport was declared fit for operation again after the Houthi forces were driven from the city, and a Saudi plane carrying aid reportedly became the first plane to land in Aden in four months.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The same day, a ship chartered by the World Food Programme carrying fuel docked in Aden's port.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Historically, Aden's harbour has been a major hub of transportation for the region.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] As of 1920, the harbour was 13 by 6 km (8 by 4 mi) in size.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Passenger ships landed at Steamer Point now called Tawahi.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] During the British colonial period motor vehicles drove on the left, as in the United Kingdom.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] On 2 January 1977, Aden, along with the rest of South Yemen, changed to driving on the right, bringing it into line with neighbouring Arab states.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] During the early 20th century, Aden was a prominent export centre for coffee grown in the Jubail highlands.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] And also to export frankincense, wheat, barley, alfalfa and millet, which are produced and exported from Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The leaves and stems of clover, millet, and corn produced in Aden were generally used as fodder.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Beginning in 1920, Aden was desalinating seawater to produce table salt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Between 1916 and 1917, Aden produced more than 120,000 tons of salt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Aden also produced potash, which was exported to Mumbai.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Historically, Aden would import goods from the African coast and from Europe, the United States, and India.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] As of 1920, the British described it as "the chief emporium of Arabian trade, receiving the small quantities of native produce, and supplying the modest wants of the interior and of most of the smaller Arabian ports." At the docks, the city provided coal to passing ships.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The only item being produced by the city, as of 1920, was salt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Also, the port was the stop ships had to take when entering the Bab-el-Mandeb; this was how cities like Mecca had received goods by ship.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Yemen Airlines, the national airline of South Yemen, had its head office in Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] On 15 May 1996, Yemen Airlines merged with Yemenia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] During the early 20th century Aden was a notable centre of coffee production.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Women processed coffee beans, grown in the Yemen highlands.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Frankincense, wheat, barley, alfalfa, and millet was also produced and exported from Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The leaves and stalks of the alfalfa, millet and maize produced in Aden were generally used as fodder.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] As of 1920, Aden was also gathering salt from salt water.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] An Italian company called Agostino Burgarella Ajola and Company gathered and process the salt under the name Aden Salt Works.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] There was also a smaller company from India, called Abdullabhoy and Joomabhoy Lalji & Company that owned a salt production firm in Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Between 1916 and 1917, Aden produced over 120,000 tons of salt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Aden has also produced potash, which was generally exported to Mumbai.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Charcoal was produced as well, from acacia, and mainly in the interior of the region.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Cigarettes were produced by Jewish and Greek populations in Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The tobacco used was imported from Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Since the outbreak of the Yemeni Civil War spread to Aden in 2015, the city has been struck by constant protests over a range of issues, but especially concerning electricity generation.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Aden's power grid is composed solely of diesel generators and is thus heavily dependent on imported fuel.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The main power plant is al-Hasswa diesel power plant, which in June 2021 had only two turbines out of five running, producing up to 50 megawatts (MW) of power in a region where the deficit hovers around 300 MW.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Nawfal al-Mojamal, the plant director, said "In its 35 years of existence, al-Hasswa station never had any kind of maintenance, except in 2016 ... when the two turbines were restored".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] This electricity shortage led to the development of Yemen's first large-scale solar power plant servicing Aden with a 120 MW capacity, opened in July 2024.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The free zone, which was opened in 1991, represents Yemen's economic gateway and the meeting point of the continents of Asia and Africa.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The free zone gains its strategic importance from the special location of the port of Aden, as it is located directly on the main trade route around the world and from the Middle East to Europe and America, and is distinguished by the possibility of providing transit services.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] To East Africa, the Red Sea, the Indian subcontinent and the Arabian Gulf.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The free zone represents a storage and distribution area suitable for Africa, the Red Sea and the Arabian Gulf.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Aden is located on the coast of the Gulf of Aden, and is about 363 kilometres from the capital, Sanaa.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] It is located between latitudes 47 and 12 north of the equator, and at an altitude of 6 metres above sea level.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] It is surrounded by Lahj Governorate to the north and east, and the Governorate of Abyan is to the northwest.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Aden has an airport (Aden International Airport), a seaport (the port of Aden), and has land routes from the north linking it to Hajj, Abyan and Taiz.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Aden is a coastal city; it overlooks the Gulf of Aden, which opens to the Indian Ocean.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The shape of the city of Aden in the form of two peninsulas helped this factor to make the city of Aden unique in this particularity, which clearly affected the occurrence of the phenomenon of land and sea breezes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Which occurs due to air exchange between land and water during the day and night.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Its location on the water surface also affects the daily and annual temperature range.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] This does not mean that there are no significant differences in temperatures in summer and winter.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Aden has a hot desert climate (BWh) in the Köppen-Geiger climate classification system.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Although Aden sees next-to-no precipitation year-round, it is humid throughout the year.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Most of the coasts of Aden Governorate along the coastal strip are sandy coasts, and the governorate has coastal beaches, including the Golden Coast in Al-Tawahi District, the coast of Abyan Bakhour Maksar, Al-Ghadeer Beach, and Kud Al-Nimr Beach in Buraiqa.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] There are about 21 islands around the peninsulas of Aden, Aden Lesser, and Ras Amran.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] They are mostly rocky islands, some of which are surrounded by incomplete coral reefs, and most of them are considered fishing areas.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] A number of islands have many activities, especially on Al-Ummal Island and Sirah Island.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Yemen is considered one of the countries rich in bird species in the Middle East due to the availability of many suitable coastal environments that helped attract many migratory birds to wetland sites, coasts and islands.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The Aden region (Khor Maksar – Al-Haswah) was registered on the list of important areas of the World Bird Organization as a habitat.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The last three species that are globally threatened with extinction are: the great eagle, the gull eagle, and the eastern king eagle.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] There are dozens of bird species recorded in the wetlands of Aden and the Caltex swamp area, which are rich in a wide variety of endemic and migratory birds, including birds that are present throughout the year.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] There are many birds in the area, including great flamingos, dwarf flamingos, and rock egrets.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] And the spoonbill, the hooked tern and the seagull.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] There are 95 schools in Aden, including 13 kindergartens, and 82 basic education schools, including 29 schools for boys, 29 schools for girls, and 29 joint schools for boys and girls.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] There are also 29 secondary schools, including 15 schools for boys and 14 schools for girls, all of which are in a double shift system.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Until 2004, the number of male students reached In basic education, there were 57,941 students and 48,081 female students, with a total of 104,622 students.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] In secondary education, the number of male students reached 11,029 students, and 9,643 female students.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] As for vocational, technical and vocational education centres and institutes, their number is 13, with 2,214 students enrolled, including 453 teachers.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The health institutes have one institute, with 864 students enrolled, including 147 teachers, according to 2010 statistics.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] As for higher education, there is one government university in Aden, which is the University of Aden, which has 9 colleges.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] More than 29 thousand students are enrolled, according to 2010 statistics.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] There are 15 hospitals in the economic capital, Aden, including 5 public government hospitals, 6 belonging to the private sector, and 37 health centres.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] There are 34 facilities in the city that provide maternity and childhood services, and the number of specialised workforce in health facilities is 2,825 specialists.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] In June 2015, the International Red Cross team present in conflict areas in Yemen during the events of the Yemeni civil war announced that the cities of Crater, Al-Mualla, Khor Maksar and Al-Tawahi in the Aden Governorate in the south of the country were areas affected by dengue fever.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The health authorities in Aden said that this fever had spread remarkably and widely.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Since the beginning of May, health services have deteriorated and infrastructure facilities, such as electricity, water, and sanitation, have been damaged as a result of the ongoing fighting in the city for months.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Aden has known mail since June 15, 1839, that is, a year after the British occupation, although the official post office was not inaugurated until 1857.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Postage stamps of both Britain and India were used in Aden until it became called the Aden Colony on April 1, 1937, although the stamps of this stage It bears no distinctive sign, but the use of the number 124 as a postal code is attributed to Aden as part of the Indian postal numerical system.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Then, when it became a colony in 1937, it had sets of postage stamps containing pictures and the name Aden printed on them.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The weekly *Al-Amal* newspaper was founded in 1957 in Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Its slogan was "Freedom, Bread, and Peace".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The British authorities allowed only 1,500 copies to be printed weekly, and the newspaper was banned shortly afterward.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] In 1958, *Al-Ayyam*, an independent daily newspaper in the Arabic language, was established in Aden during the British occupation.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The first issue was published on 30 July 1958, and its founder and editor-in-chief was Brigadier General Muhammad Ali Bashraheel.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] It stopped publishing after independence during the era of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen, and then resumed publication.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] After achieving Yemeni unity, the first issue of the second edition was on 7 November 1990, after a hiatus that lasted more than 23 years.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] In 1998, *Al-Ayyam* was the first newspaper in Yemen to be prosecuted by the government under a criminal law.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Other cases followed until it became public by the end of the year.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] 2008, responsible for 73% of the total number of cases filed by the Ministry of Information and the Yemeni government against the press in Yemen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] On 12 May 2009, security forces launched an attack on the headquarters of *Al-Ayyam* newspaper in Aden.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Radio Aden was established on 17 August 1954, under the name "Aden Radio Station".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] It is currently broadcast in two periods, morning and evening.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] The British occupation opened the Aden Channel on 11 September 1964, following the revolution of 14 October 1963.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] Television transmission was limited to covering populated neighbourhoods in the city of Aden, especially where soldiers and families of the British forces were present.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] In January 1979, the television headquarters moved to the "Radio and Television Building" in Tawahi; at that time broadcasts were in black-and-white.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] In March 1981 the gradual transition to colour broadcasting began, and in June 1981 the channel began broadcasting via satellite.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/aden-p02] After the Yemeni unification on 22 May 1990, Aden Channel was the second official channel of Yemeni TV.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The **Adena culture** was a pre-Columbian Native American culture that existed from 500 BC to 100 AD, in a time known as the Early Woodland period.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The Adena culture refers to what were probably a number of related Native American societies sharing a burial complex and ceremonial system.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The Adena culture was centered on the location of the modern state of Ohio, but also extended into contiguous areas of Kentucky, West Virginia, Indiana, Illinois, Southern Wisconsin and parts of extreme western Pennsylvania.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The Adena culture was named for the large mound on Thomas Worthington's early 19th-century estate located near Chillicothe, Ohio, which he named "Adena".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The culture is the most prominently known of a number of similar cultures in eastern North America that began mound building ceremonialism at the end of the Archaic period.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The geographic range of the Adena sites is centered on central and southern Ohio, with further sites in contiguous areas of the surrounding states of Indiana, Kentucky, West Virginia and Pennsylvania.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The importance of the Adena complex comes from its considerable influence on other contemporary cultures and cultures that came after it.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The Adena culture is seen as the precursor to the traditions of the Hopewell tradition, which are sometimes thought as an elaboration, or zenith, of Adena traditions.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The Adena were notable for their agricultural practices, pottery, artistic works, and extensive trading network, which supplied them with a variety of raw materials, ranging from copper from the Great Lakes to shells from the Gulf Coast.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Lasting traces of Adena culture are still seen in the remains of their substantial earthworks.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] At one point, larger Adena mounds numbered in the hundreds, but only a small number of the remains of the larger Adena earthen monuments still survive today.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] These mounds generally ranged in size from 20 feet (6.1 m) to 300 feet (91 m) in diameter and served as burial structures, ceremonial sites, historical markers, and possibly gathering places.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] These earthen monuments were built using hundreds of thousands of baskets full of specially selected and graded earth.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] According to archaeological investigations, Adena earthworks were often built as part of their burial rituals, in which the earth of the earthwork was piled immediately atop a burned mortuary building.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] These mortuary buildings were intended to keep and maintain the dead until their final burial was performed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Before the construction of the earthworks, some utilitarian and grave goods would be placed on the floor of the structure, which was burned with the goods and honored dead within.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The earthwork would then be constructed, and often a new mortuary structure would be placed atop the new earthwork.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] After a series of repetitions, mortuary/earthwork/mortuary/earthwork, a quite prominent earthwork would remain.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] In the later Adena period, circular ridges of unknown function were sometimes constructed around the burial earthworks.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The Great Serpent Mound in Ohio has been attributed to this culture, however, without conclusive evidence.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Their mounds are similar to mounds built in Sweden during the end of the Bronze age.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The Adena also carved small stone tablets, usually 4 or 5 inches by 3 or 4 inches by .5 inches thick.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] On one or both flat sides were gracefully composed stylized zoomorphs or curvilinear geometric designs in deep relief.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Paint has been found on some Adena tablets, leading archaeologists to propose that these stone tablets were probably used to stamp designs on cloth or animal hides, or onto their own bodies.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] It is possible that they were used to outline designs for tattooing.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Postholes from a number of timber circles have been found during excavations of Adena culture causewayed ring ditch sites in the Bluegrass region of Kentucky and adjacent regions of Ohio and West Virginia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] A notable example was found by archaeologist William S.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Webb during the excavations of the Mount Horeb Site 1 in Fayette County, Kentucky in 1939.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Webb discovered a circle of "paired-posts" inside of the embankment ring and ditch.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The 48.5 feet (14.8 m) circle was made up of sixty two "paired" post sets and eight single posts.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Unlike in other cultures, Adena pottery was not buried with the dead or the remains of the cremated, as were other artifacts.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Usually Adena pottery was tempered with grit or crushed limestone and was very thick; its decoration was largely plain, cord-marked or fabric marked, although one type bore a nested-diamond design incised into its surface.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The vessel shapes were sub-conoidal or flat-bottomed jars, sometimes with small foot-like supports.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The large and elaborate mound sites served a nearby scattering of people.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The population was dispersed in small settlements of one to two structures.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] A typical house was built in a circle form from 15 to 45 feet in diameter.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The walls were made of paired posts tilted outward, that were then joined to other pieces of wood to form a cone shaped roof.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] The roof was then covered with bark and the walls may have been bark and/or wickerwork.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Their sustenance was acquired through foraging and the cultivation of native plants.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Somewhat rougher slab-like stones with chipped edges were probably used as hoes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Bone and antler were used in small tools, but even more prominently in ornamental objects such as beads, combs, and worked animal-jaw gorgets or paraphernalia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] Spoons, beads and other implements were made from the marine conch.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/adena-culture] A few copper axes have been found, but otherwise the metal was hammered into ornamental forms, such as bracelets, rings, beads, and reel-shaped pendants.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Maritime history dates back thousands of years.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The earliest watercraft used by humans were rafts, as they needed less sophisticated wood-working skills to make.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The oldest archaeological survival of a prehistoric boat is a dugout canoe, the Pesse canoe, which dates to approximately 10,000 years ago.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Dugouts probably coexisted with hide-covered boats, which are much less likely to survive for archaeological investigation.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Some evidence suggests that archaic hominins may have crossed the sea as early as 700,000 to one million years ago.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] In ancient maritime history, evidence of maritime trade between civilizations dates back at least five millennia.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Egyptians had trade routes through the Red Sea, importing spices from the "Land of Punt" and from Arabia, and the Sumerians traded with the Indus Valley civilization around the same time.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] By the time of Julius Caesar of the Roman Empire, several well-established combined land-sea trade routes depended upon water transport through the sea around the rough inland terrain features to its north.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The search for the source of spices in these maritime trade routes later led to the Age of Discovery.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The earliest seafaring is presumed to have developed in the "nursery" areas of Island Southeast Asia (ISEA) and the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Both ISEA and the Mediterranean had a warm climate and, particularly in the former, large numbers of intervisible islands; both assisted early seafarers.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Water transport also developed on major rivers, such as the Nile.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The first watercraft are likely to have been rafts, as these make less demands on the woodworking skills of pre-neolithic builders.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Rafts or hide-covered boats (e.g. coracle) have a low probability of surviving in an archaeological site; there are historical instances of rafts being dismantled after use and the components being used for other purposes, further reducing the chances of archaeological survival.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Therefore, maritime transport has to be inferred from evidence such as human migration which cannot have been carried out by land, even in cases of lowered sea levels due to extensive glaciation.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Other presumed evidence of water transport has proved problematic.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Excavated bones of pelagic fish species (such as tuna) have been erroneously interpreted as demonstrating deep-sea fishing.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Prior to fish stocks being reduced by commercial fishing, these species have been readily caught where deep water exists close to the shoreline.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The invention (or adoption) of the sail is believed to have happened quite late in the prehistory of maritime transport, coinciding with other changes in the process of neolithicisation.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Iconographic evidence of sail in Egypt dates to the late fourth millennium BC, and there is suggestive evidence in the eastern Mediterranean and the Persian Gulf in the late third millennium BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] These advances in water transport are broadly contemporaneous with wheeled transport pulled by draught animals (examples c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The invention of new forms of transport technology, both at sea and on land, have posed questions about relationships between the processes that have come into play with each development.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Whilst the invention of the sail may appear obvious to a modern seafarer, its introduction and then spread into other regions (or the independent invention in those regions) happened slowly.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] From the eastern Mediterranean and Red Sea/Persian Gulf c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] 2500 BC, expansion into the central Mediterranean and the west coast of India happened c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Eastward spread into the Bay of Bengal and Island Southeast Asia has been dated to c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] 1000 BC, with spread into the western Mediterranean at about the same time.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Northern Europe, excluding Nordic countries, has evidence of sail use from the early years AD, whilst Scandinavia appears not to have used sails until late in the first millennium AD.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Sailing was not used in the Caribbean until the arrival of Columbus' ships in 1492.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Whether the sail was invented on different occasions in different places is difficult to assess, with diffusionist theories falling in and out of fashion.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] One instance of independent invention may be in the region of the Guayaquil river in modern Ecuador.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Sails of a relatively unique design were being used when Europeans first arrived in the area in the 16th century.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The geography of the Guayaquil river is reminiscent of that of the Nile, with the prevailing wind going in the opposite direction to the flow of the river.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This allows drifting downstream and sailing upstream: a suitable situation to encourage invention of sailing.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The lowered sea levels of the Pleistocene made some of the modern-day islands of Sundaland accessible via land bridges.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] However, the spread of anatomically modern humans across the Wallace line and into Sahul necessitated crossing bodies of water.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Remains of stone tools and marine shells in Liang Sarru, Salibabu Island, North Sulawesi, dated to 32,000–35,000 years ago, is possible evidence for the longest sea voyage by Paleolithic humans ever recorded.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The island was previously uninhabited by humans or hominins and can only be reached from either Mindanao or the Sangihe Islands by crossing an expanse of water at least 100 km (62 mi) wide, even during the low sea levels of the Pleistocene.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Other evidence of early maritime transport are the appearance of obsidian tools with the same source on neighboring islands.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] These include the Philippine obsidian network (Mindoro and Palawan, c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] 33,000-28,000 BP), and the Wallacea obsidian network (Timor, Atauro, Kisar, Alor, c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] However, the method of crossing remains unknown and could have ranged from simple rafts to dugout canoes by the terminal Pleistocene.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The sea crossing by humans to the Sahul landmass (modern Australia and New Guinea) from the Sundaland peninsula occurred around 53,000 to 65,000 years ago.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Even with the lower sea level of that time, this crossing would have involved travelling out of sight of land – the overall distances involved at the possible crossing points are all over 55 miles.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] It is likely that large bamboo rafts were used, possibly with a sail of some sort.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Up until 58,000 BP, the winds during the Northern Australian wet season were particularly favourable for making this crossing (relevant even without sails).
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The reduction in favourable winds after that date fits well with the single colonisation phase of Australia during prehistory.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] In the history of whaling, humans are believed to have begun whaling in Korea at least 6000 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The oldest known method of catching whales is to simply drive them ashore by placing a number of small boats between the whale and the open sea and attempting to frighten them with noise, activity, and perhaps small, non-lethal weapons such as arrows.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Austronesians used distinctive sailing technologies, namely the catamaran, the outrigger ship, tanja sail and the crab claw sail.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This allowed them to colonize a large part of the Indo-Pacific region during the Austronesian expansion starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC, and ending with the colonization of Easter Island and New Zealand in the 10th to 13th centuries AD.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Prior to the 16th century Colonial Era, Austronesians were the most widespread ethnolinguistic group, spanning half the planet from Easter Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean to Madagascar in the western Indian Ocean.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] They also established vast maritime trading networks, among which is the Neolithic precursor to what would become the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The acquisition of the catamaran and outrigger boat technology by the non-Austronesian peoples in Sri Lanka and southern India is the result of Austronesian contact with the region, including the Maldives and Laccadive Islands.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This is estimated to have occurred around 1000 to 600 BC and onwards, and led to the development of India and Sri Lanka's own maritime trade networks.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This may have possibly included limited colonization that have since been assimilated.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This is still evident in Sri Lankan and South Indian languages.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This led to the development of China's own maritime technologies later on, during the Song dynasty in the 10th to 13th century AD.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] At the furthest extents of the Austronesian expansion, colonists from Borneo crossed the Indian Ocean westward to settle in Madagascar and the Comoros by around 500 AD.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] In the east, the first true ocean voyage was the colonization of the Northern Marianas Islands of Micronesia from the Philippines.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This was followed by more migrations southwards and eastwards to Island Melanesia up to islands beyond the inter-island visibility range like Tonga and Samoa.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This region was occupied by the Austronesian Lapita culture.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] After a gap of about two thousand years, the first Polynesians continued spreading eastwards into the Cook Islands, French Polynesia, Hawaii, Easter Island, and Aotearoa, New Zealand by around AD 700 to 1200.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Austronesian seafarers used environmental navigation systems: orientation at sea is carried out using a variety of different natural signs, and by using an astronomy technique called "star path navigation".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Basically, the navigators determined the course of the ship to the destination by recognising the rising and setting positions of certain stars on the horizon.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Māori people of New Zealand are said to have Navigated following the zodiacal constellation of Scorpio, between Libra and Sagittarius in the southern sky positioned at about 16 hours 30 minutes right ascension and 30° south declination to find, Aotearoa, "The Land of the Long, White, Cloud".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Each major route involved transhipping to pack animal caravan, travel through desert country and risk of bandits and extortionate tolls by local potentiates.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Maritime trade began with safer coastal trade and evolved with the utilization of the monsoon winds, soon resulting in trade crossing boundaries such as the Arabian Sea and the Bay of Bengal.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] South Asia had multiple maritime trade routes which connected it to Southeast Asia, thereby making the control of one route resulting in maritime monopoly difficult.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Indian traders had a choice of routes to Southeast Asian states, so protecting them from one power controlling trade that went through their territory.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] By making use of the maritime trade routes, bulk commodity trade became possible for the Romans in the 2nd century BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] A Roman trading vessel could span the Mediterranean in a month at one-sixtieth the cost of over-land routes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Ancient Egyptians had knowledge of sail construction.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The first warships of Ancient Egypt were constructed during the early Middle Kingdom, and perhaps – at the end of the Old Kingdom, but the first mention and a detailed description of a large enough and heavily armed ship dates from 16th century BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] "And I ordered to build twelve warships with rams, dedicated to Amun or Sobek, or Maat and Sekhmet, whose image was crowned best bronze noses.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Carport and equipped outside rook over the waters, for many paddlers, having covered rowers deck not only from the side, but and top. and they were on board eighteen oars in two rows on the top and sat on two rowers, and the lower – one, a hundred and eight rowers were.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] And twelve rowers aft worked on three steering oars.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] And blocked Our Majesty ship inside three partitions (bulkheads) so as not to drown it by ramming the wicked, and the sailors had time to repair the hole.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] When Thutmose III achieved warships displacement up to 360 tons and carried up to ten new heavy and light to seventeen catapults based bronze springs, called "siege crossbow" – more precisely, siege bows.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Still appeared giant catamarans that are heavy warships and times of Ramesses III used even when the Ptolemaic dynasty.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] According to the Greek historian Herodotus, Necho II sent out an expedition of Phoenicians, which reputedly, at some point between 610 and before 594 BC, sailed in three years from the Red Sea around Africa to the mouth of the Nile.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Some Egyptologists dispute that an Egyptian Pharaoh would authorize such an expedition, except for the reason of trade in the ancient maritime routes.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] So fantastic an assertion is this of a typical example of some seafarers' story and Herodotus therefore may never have mentioned it, at all, had it not been based on facts and made with the according insistence.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This early description of Necho's expedition as a whole is contentious, though; it is recommended that one keep an open mind on the subject; but Strabo, Polybius, and Ptolemy doubted the description.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Lloyd suggests that the Greeks at this time understood that anyone going south far enough and then turning west would have the Sun on their right but found it unbelievable that Africa reached so far south.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] He suggests that "It is extremely unlikely that an Egyptian king would, or could, have acted as Necho is depicted as doing" and that the story might have been triggered by the failure of Sataspes' attempt to circumnavigate Africa under Xerxes the Great.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Regardless, it was believed by Herodotus and Pliny.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Much earlier, the Sea Peoples was a confederacy of seafaring raiders who sailed into the eastern shores of the Mediterranean, caused political unrest, and attempted to enter or control Egyptian territory during the late 19th dynasty, and especially during Year 8 of Ramesses III of the 20th Dynasty.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Egyptian Pharaoh Merneptah explicitly refers to them by the term "the foreign-countries (or 'peoples') of the sea" in his Great Karnak Inscription.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Although some scholars believe that they "invaded" Cyprus and the Levant, this hypothesis is disputed.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] In ancient times the Kingdom of Punt, which is believed by several Egyptologists to have been situated in the area of modern-day Somalia, had a steady trade link with the Ancient Egyptians and exported the precious natural resources such as myrrh, frankincense and gum.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This trade network continued all the way into the classical era.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The city states of Mossylon, Opone, Malao, Mundus and Tabae in Somalia engaged in a lucrative trade network connecting Somali merchants with Phoenicia, Ptolemic Egypt, Greece, Parthian Persia, Saba, Nabataea and the Roman Empire.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Somali sailors used the ancient Somali maritime vessel known as the *beden* to transport their cargo.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Minoan traders from Crete were active in the eastern Mediterranean by the 2nd millennium BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Phoenicians were an ancient civilization centered in the north of ancient Canaan, with its heartland along the coast of modern-day Lebanon, Western Syria and northern Israel.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Phoenician civilization was an enterprising maritime trading culture that spread across the Mediterranean during the first millennium BC, between the period of 1200 BC to 900 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The recent discovery of three shipwrecks off the coast of Israel provides new insights into the history of maritime trade during the Iron Age.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Though ancient boundaries of such city-centered cultures fluctuated, the city of Tyre seems to have been the southernmost.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Sarepta between Sidon and Tyre, is the most thoroughly excavated city of the Phoenician homeland.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Phoenicians often traded by means of a galley, a man-powered sailing vessel.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] They were the first civilization to create the bireme.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] There is still debate on the subject of whether the Canaanites and Phoenicians were different peoples or not.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Mediterranean was the source of the vessel, galley, developed before 1000 BC, and development of nautical technology supported the expansion of Mediterranean culture.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Greek trireme was the most common ship of the ancient Mediterranean world, employing the propulsion power of oarsmen.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Mediterranean peoples developed lighthouse technology and built large fire-based lighthouses, most notably the Lighthouse of Alexandria, built in the 3rd century BC (between 285 and 247 BC) on the island of Pharos in Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Many in ancient western societies, such as Ancient Greece, were in awe of the seas and deified them, believing that man no longer belonged to himself when once he embarked on a sea voyage.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] They believed that he was liable to be sacrificed at any time to the anger of the great Sea God.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Before the Greeks, the Carians were an early Mediterranean seagoing people that travelled far.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Early writers do not give a good idea about the progress of navigation nor that of the man's seamanship.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] One of the early stories of seafaring was that of Odysseus.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] In Greek mythology, the Argonauts were a band of heroes who, in the years before the Trojan War, accompanied Jason to Colchis in his quest to find the Golden Fleece.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Their name comes from their ship, the Argo which in turn was named after its builder Argus.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Thus, "Argonauts" literally means "Argo sailors".
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The voyage of the Greek navigator Pytheas of Massalia is an example of a very early voyage.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] A competent astronomer and geographer, Pytheas ventured from Greece to Western Europe and the British Isles.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The *periplus*, literally "a sailing-around', in the ancient navigation of Phoenicians, Greeks, and Romans was a manuscript document that listed in order the ports and coastal landmarks, with approximate distances between, that the captain of a vessel could expect to find along a shore.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Several examples of *periploi* have survived.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The earliest seagoing culture in the Mediterranean is associated with Cardium pottery.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Their earliest impressed ware sites, dating to 6400–6200 BC, are in Epirus and Corfu.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Settlements then appear in Albania and Dalmatia on the eastern Adriatic coast dating to between 6100 and 5900 BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The earliest date in Italy comes from Coppa Nevigata on the Adriatic coast of southern Italy, perhaps as early as 6000 cal B.C.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Also during Su Carroppu culture in Sardinia, already in its early stages (low strata into Su Coloru cave, c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] 6000 BC) early examples of cardium pottery appear.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Northward and westward all secure radiocarbon dates are identical to those for Iberia c.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] 5500 cal BC, which indicates a rapid spread of cardium and related cultures: 2,000 km from the gulf of Genoa to the estuary of the Mondego in probably no more than 100–200 years.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This suggests a seafaring expansion by planting colonies along the coast.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] In Ionia (the modern Aegean coast of Turkey) the Greek cities, which included great centres such as Miletus and Halicarnassus, were unable to maintain their independence and came under the rule of the Persian Empire in the mid-6th century BC.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] In 499 BC the Greeks rose in the Ionian Revolt, and Athens and some other Greek cities went to their aid.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] In 490 BC, the Persian Great King, Darius I, having suppressed the Ionian cities, sent a fleet to punish the Greeks.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Persians landed in Attica, but were defeated at the Battle of Marathon by a Greek army led by the Athenian general Miltiades.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The burial mound of the Athenian dead can still be seen at Marathon.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Ten years later Darius' successor, Xerxes I, sent a much more powerful force by land.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] After being delayed by the Spartan King Leonidas I at Thermopylae, Xerxes advanced into Attica, where he captured and burned Athens.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] But the Athenians had evacuated the city by sea, and under Themistocles they defeated the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] A year later, the Greeks, under the Spartan Pausanias, defeated the Persian army at Plataea.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Athenian fleet then turned to chasing the Persians out of the Aegean Sea, and in 478 BC they captured Byzantium.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] In the course of doing so Athens enrolled all the island states and some mainland allies into an alliance, called the Delian League because its treasury was kept on the sacred island of Delos.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Spartans, although they had taken part in the war, withdrew into isolation after it, allowing Athens to establish unchallenged naval and commercial power.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Punic Wars were a series of three wars fought between Rome and Carthage.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The main cause of the Punic Wars was the clash of interests between the existing Carthaginian Empire and the expanding Roman sphere of influence.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Romans were initially interested in expansion via Sicily, part of which lay under Carthaginian control.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] At the start of the first Punic War, Carthage was the dominant power of the Mediterranean, with an extensive maritime empire, while Rome was the rapidly ascending power in Italy.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] By the end of the third war, after the deaths of many hundreds of thousands of soldiers from both sides, Rome had conquered Carthage's empire and razed the city, becoming in the process the most powerful state of the Western Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] This was a turning point that meant that the civilization of the ancient Mediterranean would pass to the modern world via Europe instead of Africa.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Coracle, a small single-passenger-sized float, has been used in Britain since before the first Roman invasion as noted by the invaders.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Coracles are round or oval in shape, made of a wooden frame with a hide stretched over it then tarred to provide waterproofing.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Being so light, an operator can carry the light craft over the shoulder.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] They are capable of operating in mere inches of water due to the keel-less hull.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The early people of Wales used these boats for fishing and light travel and updated models are still in use to this day on the rivers of Scotland and Wales.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Early Britons also used the dugout canoe.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Examples of these canoes have been found buried in marshes and mud banks of rivers at lengths of upward eight feet.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] In 1992 a notable archaeological find, named the "Dover Bronze Age Boat", was unearthed from beneath what is modern day Dover, England.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] The Bronze Age boat which is about 9.5 meters long × 2.3 meters wide is believed to have been a seagoing vessel.
[src:ancient-maritime-history/ancient-maritime-history] Carbon dating reveals that the craft dating from approximately 1600 BC might be the oldest known sea-going boat.
